% @category: Advanced Programmability & Terminal
% @name: Computational Lambdas
% @description: A powerful compiled language within Hyades
@cassilda: cl_guide
  Hyades has two programmability systems. The first – macros – is a text substitu-
  tion  engine,  the  subject  of  a separate  guide. The  second is Computational
  Lambdas (CL), a fully typed  computational layer compiled to bytecode and execu-
  ted by the  Subnivean virtual machine. Where macros  transform text, CL computes
  values:  integers, strings, arrays, hash maps, heap memory, and  terminal output
  fast enough for interactive applications.
  
  This guide builds progressively from a first lambda to complete programs. By the
  end  you will  understand every  feature CL offers – and you  will have  seen it
  drive  Conway’s Game of Life and a Matrix Digital Rain, both running live inside
  a typesetting engine.
  
  The  sections build on each  other, so reading  front to back is recommended.  A
  Quick Reference table at the end covers every command in one place.
  
  𝐘𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐅𝐢𝐫𝐬𝐭 𝐋𝐚𝐦𝐛𝐝𝐚
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  A 𝑙𝑎𝑚𝑏𝑑𝑎 is a named function. The simplest form takes no parameters  and returns
  a constant:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<greet>#{                                                      │
  │ 2:  │      \return{42}                                                       │
  │ 3:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  Result: \invoke<greet>[]                                              │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Result: 42                                                           ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Three things to notice.  First, the # before the opening brace – it tells Hyades
  to compile  this body to Subnivean  bytecode instead of interpreting it as text.
  Second, \𝑟𝑒𝑡𝑢𝑟𝑛  provides the value  that flows  back to the  call site.  Third,
  \𝑖𝑛𝑣𝑜𝑘𝑒<name>[args] is the calling  convention: the name goes in angle brackets,
  arguments in square brackets (empty here because 𝑔𝑟𝑒𝑒𝑡 takes none).
  
  Without the #, the body would be treated as a macro – text substitution, not co-
  mputation. The # is the gateway to everything in this guide.
  
            ............................................................
                                TWO KINDS OF LAMBDA
  
            A lambda  body in plain braces {…} is interpreted as text by
            the macro engine. A lambda body in #{…} is compiled to byte-
            code by Subnivean.  Both are defined with  \𝑙𝑎𝑚𝑏𝑑𝑎, but they
            live in different worlds. This guide covers #{} exclusively.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐅𝐮𝐧𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐏𝐚𝐫𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Lambdas accept typed parameters in square brackets:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<ADD>[a:int, b:int]#{                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \return{\add{${a}, ${b}}}                                         │
  │ 3:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  \invoke<ADD>[3, 4] \\                                                 │
  │ 6:  │  \invoke<ADD>[100, 200]                                                │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   7                                                                    ░│
     │   300                                                                  ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Each parameter carries a type  annotation: 𝑎:𝑖𝑛𝑡 declares a parameter named 𝑎 of
  type 𝑖𝑛𝑡. The available types are covered in the next section.
  
  Functions can call other functions. Because each lambda is a named, global enti-
  ty, any lambda can invoke any other:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<SQUARE>[x:int]#{                                              │
  │ 2:  │      \return{\mul{${x}, ${x}}}                                         │
  │ 3:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  \lambda<SUM_OF_SQUARES>[a:int, b:int]#{                               │
  │ 6:  │      \return{\add{                                                     │
  │ 7:  │          \invoke<SQUARE>[${a}],                                        │
  │ 8:  │          \invoke<SQUARE>[${b}]                                         │
  │ 9:  │      }}                                                                │
  │ 10: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 11: │                                                                        │
  │ 12: │  $3^2 + 4^2$ = \invoke<SUM_OF_SQUARES>[3, 4]                           │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │    2    2                                                              ░│
     │   3  + 4  = 25                                                         ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  \𝑖𝑛𝑣𝑜𝑘𝑒 calls nest freely. Here 𝑆𝑈𝑀_𝑂𝐹_𝑆𝑄𝑈𝐴𝑅𝐸𝑆 calls 𝑆𝑄𝑈𝐴𝑅𝐸 twice, and the resu-
  lts flow back through the \𝑎𝑑𝑑.
  
  
  𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐓𝐲𝐩𝐞 𝐒𝐲𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐦
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  CL has six types. Every variable must be typed on its first  declaration; subse-
  quent reassignments may omit the type:
  
    ● 𝐢𝐧𝐭 – 64-bit signed integer, the workhorse type
    ● 𝐬𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 – immutable UTF-8 text
    ● 𝐢𝐧𝐭[] – mutable integer array
    ● 𝐬𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠[] – mutable string array
    ● 𝐦𝐚𝐩 – Robin Hood hash map (integer keys and values)
    ● 𝐚𝐝𝐝𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐬 – a handle to a collection, for passing by reference
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<TYPES>[]#{                                                    │
  │ 2:  │      \let<x:int>{42}                                                   │
  │ 3:  │      \let<s:string>{hello}                                             │
  │ 4:  │      \let<arr:int[]>{[10, 20, 30]}                                     │
  │ 5:  │      \let<m:map>{|1->100, 2->200|}                                     │
  │ 6:  │                                                                        │
  │ 7:  │      \let<x>{99}   % reassign: type already known                      │
  │ 8:  │      \return{${x}}                                                     │
  │ 9:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 10: │                                                                        │
  │ 11: │  \invoke<TYPES>[]                                                      │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   99                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Variable  access is always {name} – the same syntax as the macro  system, so mu-
  scle memory transfers directly.
  
            ............................................................
                                OLD SYNTAX IS BANNED
  
            Inside #{} blocks, the old \𝑣𝑎𝑙𝑢𝑒𝑜𝑓<x> and \𝑟𝑒𝑐𝑎𝑙𝑙<x> comma-
            nds are rejected by the parser with helpful error  messages.
            This  keeps CL code  clean and  unambiguous. The old  syntax
            still works in regular macro bodies.
            ............................................................
                           Type Annotations on Parameters
                         o════════════════════════════════o
  
  Parameters carry the same type annotations. The type goes after a colon:
  
  ┌────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │                1:  │  \lambda<fn>[name:type, name:type]#{ ... }              │
  └────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The type tells Subnivean how to allocate storage and which operations are valid.
  Passing  the wrong type  causes a runtime  coercion – integers  convert to their
  string  representation, strings parse to integers  when possible  (defaulting to
  0).
  
                                    Reassignment
                                  o══════════════o
  
  After the first \𝑙𝑒𝑡 with a type, later assignments omit it:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<x:int>{1}        % first time: typed                             │
  │ 2:  │  \let<x>{2}            % reassign: type known                          │
  │ 3:  │  \let<x>{\add{${x},3}} % computed reassignment                         │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  Attempting to re-declare the type is harmless but unnecessary.
  
  
  𝐀𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐡𝐦𝐞𝐭𝐢𝐜, 𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐬𝐨𝐧, 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐋𝐨𝐠𝐢𝐜
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  CL provides the same  operators available in the macro system. Inside #{} blocks
  they  compile to direct  bytecode  operations instead of text  expansion, making
  them substantially faster.
  
                                     Arithmetic
                                   o════════════o
    ● \𝑎𝑑𝑑{a,b}:  addition
    ● \𝑠𝑢𝑏{a,b}:  subtraction
    ● \𝑚𝑢𝑙{a,b}:  multiplication
    ● \𝑑𝑖𝑣{a,b}:  integer division (rounds toward zero)
    ● \𝑚𝑜𝑑{a,b}:  remainder after division
    ● \𝑛𝑒𝑔{a}:  negation (-𝑎)
    ● \𝑚𝑎𝑥{a,b}:  the larger value
    ● \𝑚𝑖𝑛{a,b}:  the smaller value
    ● \𝑟𝑎𝑛𝑑{n}:  random integer in [0, 𝑛)
                                    Comparisons
                                  o═════════════o
  
  All comparisons return 1 for true, 0 for false:
  
    ● \𝑒𝑞{a,b}, \𝑛𝑒{a,b}:  equal, not equal
    ● \𝑙𝑡{a,b}, \𝑙𝑒{a,b}:  less than, less-or-equal
    ● \𝑔𝑡{a,b}, \𝑔𝑒{a,b}:  greater than, greater-or-equal
                                       Logic
                                     o═══════o
    ● \𝑎𝑛𝑑{a,b}:  logical AND (1 iff both nonzero)
    ● \𝑜𝑟{a,b}:  logical OR (1 iff either nonzero)
    ● \𝑛𝑜𝑡{a}:  logical NOT (1 if zero, 0 if nonzero)
  
  These nest naturally. A condition like “x is between 1 and 100” reads:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<IN_RANGE>[x:int]#{                                            │
  │ 2:  │      \return{\and{\ge{${x}, 1}, \le{${x}, 100}}}                       │
  │ 3:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  in range: \invoke<IN_RANGE>[42] \\                                    │
  │ 6:  │  out of range: \invoke<IN_RANGE>[200]                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   in range: 1                                                          ░│
     │   out of range: 0                                                      ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  
  𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐥 𝐅𝐥𝐨𝐰
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
                                    Conditionals
                                  o══════════════o
  
  The \𝑖𝑓/\𝑒𝑙𝑠𝑒 structure works identically to the macro system:
  
  ┌─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │             1:  │  \if{condition}{true branch}\else{false branch}            │
  └─────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  Zero is false, every other  integer is true. The \𝑒𝑙𝑠𝑒  branch is optional.  The
  placement rule applies here too: \𝑒𝑙𝑠𝑒 must immediately follow the closing brace
  of the true branch with no intervening whitespace.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<ABS>[x:int]#{                                                 │
  │ 2:  │      \if{\lt{${x}, 0}}{                                                │
  │ 3:  │          \return{\sub{0, ${x}}}                                        │
  │ 4:  │      }\else{                                                           │
  │ 5:  │          \return{${x}}                                                 │
  │ 6:  │      }                                                                 │
  │ 7:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 8:  │                                                                        │
  │ 9:  │  abs(-42) = \invoke<ABS>[-42] \\                                       │
  │ 10: │  abs(7) = \invoke<ABS>[7]                                              │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   abs(-42) = 42                                                        ░│
     │   abs(7) = 7                                                           ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Conditionals  nest for multi-way  branching. A nested  chain acts  like a switch
  statement:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<CLASSIFY>[n:int]#{                                            │
  │ 2:  │      \if{\lt{${n}, 0}}{                                                │
  │ 3:  │          \return{-1}                                                   │
  │ 4:  │      }\else{\if{\eq{${n}, 0}}{                                         │
  │ 5:  │          \return{0}                                                    │
  │ 6:  │      }\else{                                                           │
  │ 7:  │          \return{1}                                                    │
  │ 8:  │      }}                                                                │
  │ 9:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 10: │                                                                        │
  │ 11: │  sign(-5) = \invoke<CLASSIFY>[-5] \\                                   │
  │ 12: │  sign(0) = \invoke<CLASSIFY>[0] \\                                     │
  │ 13: │  sign(99) = \invoke<CLASSIFY>[99]                                      │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   sign(-5) = -1                                                        ░│
     │   sign(0) = 0                                                          ░│
     │   sign(99) = 1                                                         ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
                                       Loops
                                     o═══════o
  
  The loop construct runs a body repeatedly until an exit condition fires:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \begin{loop}                                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \exit_when{condition}                                             │
  │ 3:  │      body                                                              │
  │ 4:  │  \end{loop}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  \𝑒𝑥𝑖𝑡_𝑤ℎ𝑒𝑛  checks its condition at the top of every  iteration. When the condi-
  tion becomes true, control jumps past \𝑒𝑛𝑑{loop} immediately – the body does not
  execute for that iteration.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<FACTORIAL>[n:int]#{                                           │
  │ 2:  │      \let<result:int>{1}                                               │
  │ 3:  │      \let<i:int>{${n}}                                                 │
  │ 4:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 5:  │          \exit_when{\le{${i}, 1}}                                      │
  │ 6:  │          \let<result>{\mul{${result}, ${i}}}                           │
  │ 7:  │          \dec<i>                                                       │
  │ 8:  │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 9:  │      \return{${result}}                                                │
  │ 10: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 11: │                                                                        │
  │ 12: │  5! = \invoke<FACTORIAL>[5] \\                                         │
  │ 13: │  10! = \invoke<FACTORIAL>[10]                                          │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   5! = 120                                                             ░│
     │   10! = 3628800                                                        ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Loops are the primary iteration  mechanism. There is no for loop or while loop –
  \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛{loop} with \𝑒𝑥𝑖𝑡_𝑤ℎ𝑒𝑛 covers all cases. The pattern is always: initialize
  a counter before the loop, test it with \𝑒𝑥𝑖𝑡_𝑤ℎ𝑒𝑛, and advance it in the body.
  
  Here is the iterative Fibonacci sequence, an accumulator pattern:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<FIB>[n:int]#{                                                 │
  │ 2:  │      \if{\le{${n}, 1}}{                                                │
  │ 3:  │          \return{${n}}                                                 │
  │ 4:  │      }                                                                 │
  │ 5:  │      \let<a:int>{0}                                                    │
  │ 6:  │      \let<b:int>{1}                                                    │
  │ 7:  │      \let<i:int>{2}                                                    │
  │ 8:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 9:  │          \exit_when{\gt{${i}, ${n}}}                                   │
  │ 10: │          \let<temp:int>{${b}}                                          │
  │ 11: │          \let<b>{\add{${a}, ${b}}}                                     │
  │ 12: │          \let<a>{${temp}}                                              │
  │ 13: │          \inc<i>                                                       │
  │ 14: │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 15: │      \return{${b}}                                                     │
  │ 16: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 17: │                                                                        │
  │ 18: │  fib(0) = \invoke<FIB>[0] \\                                           │
  │ 19: │  fib(1) = \invoke<FIB>[1] \\                                           │
  │ 20: │  fib(10) = \invoke<FIB>[10]                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   fib(0) = 0                                                           ░│
     │   fib(1) = 1                                                           ░│
     │   fib(10) = 55                                                         ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The guard  clause at the top  handles the base cases with an early  \𝑟𝑒𝑡𝑢𝑟𝑛. The
  accumulator  loop then slides two variables forward through the sequence without
  recursion.
  
  One more classic: the Euclidean GCD.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<GCD>[a:int, b:int]#{                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \let<x:int>{${a}}                                                 │
  │ 3:  │      \let<y:int>{${b}}                                                 │
  │ 4:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 5:  │          \exit_when{\eq{${y}, 0}}                                      │
  │ 6:  │          \let<temp:int>{\mod{${x}, ${y}}}                              │
  │ 7:  │          \let<x>{${y}}                                                 │
  │ 8:  │          \let<y>{${temp}}                                              │
  │ 9:  │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 10: │      \return{${x}}                                                     │
  │ 11: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 12: │                                                                        │
  │ 13: │  gcd(48, 18) = \invoke<GCD>[48, 18] \\                                 │
  │ 14: │  gcd(100, 25) = \invoke<GCD>[100, 25]                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   gcd(48, 18) = 6                                                      ░│
     │   gcd(100, 25) = 25                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The algorithm repeatedly replaces the pair (𝑥, 𝑦) with (𝑦, 𝑥 mod 𝑦) until 𝑦 rea-
  ches zero. At that point 𝑥 holds the greatest common divisor.
  
            ............................................................
                                    EARLY RETURN
  
            \𝑟𝑒𝑡𝑢𝑟𝑛 is not  limited to the  end of a function.  It exits
            the  current lambda  immediately from  wherever it appears –
            inside a loop, inside a conditional,  anywhere. This is use-
            ful for guard clauses:
  
            ┌─────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
            │ 1:  │  \lambda<SAFE_DIV>[a:int, b:int]#{
            │ 2:  │      \if{\eq{${b}, 0}}{\return{0}}
            │ 3:  │      \return{\div{${a}, ${b}}}
            │ 4:  │  }
            └─────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐀𝐫𝐫𝐚𝐲𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Arrays  are ordered, mutable  sequences with O(1) random  access. Declare one by
  appending [] to the type name:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<ARRAY_SUM>[]#{                                                │
  │ 2:  │      \let<nums:int[]>{[10, 20, 30, 40, 50]}                            │
  │ 3:  │      \let<sum:int>{0}                                                  │
  │ 4:  │      \let<i:int>{0}                                                    │
  │ 5:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 6:  │          \exit_when{\ge{${i}, \len<nums>}}                             │
  │ 7:  │          \let<sum>{\add{${sum}, \at<nums>[${i}]}}                      │
  │ 8:  │          \inc<i>                                                       │
  │ 9:  │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 10: │      \return{${sum}}                                                   │
  │ 11: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 12: │                                                                        │
  │ 13: │  Sum: \invoke<ARRAY_SUM>[]                                             │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Sum: 150                                                             ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The key operations:
  
    ● \𝑎𝑡<arr>[index] – read an element
    ● \𝑠𝑒𝑡<arr>[index]{value} – write an element
    ● \𝑙𝑒𝑛<arr> – the number of elements
  
  Array indices are  zero-based. Reading past the end  returns 0; writing past the
  end is silently ignored.
  
                                 Finding a Maximum
                               o═══════════════════o
  
  A common pattern: iterate an array tracking the best value seen so far.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<FIND_MAX>[]#{                                                 │
  │ 2:  │      \let<arr:int[]>{[34, 12, 78, 5, 91, 23]}                          │
  │ 3:  │      \let<best:int>{\at<arr>[0]}                                       │
  │ 4:  │      \let<i:int>{1}                                                    │
  │ 5:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 6:  │          \exit_when{\ge{${i}, \len<arr>}}                              │
  │ 7:  │          \if{\gt{\at<arr>[${i}], ${best}}}{                            │
  │ 8:  │              \let<best>{\at<arr>[${i}]}                                │
  │ 9:  │          }                                                             │
  │ 10: │          \inc<i>                                                       │
  │ 11: │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 12: │      \return{${best}}                                                  │
  │ 13: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 14: │                                                                        │
  │ 15: │  Maximum: \invoke<FIND_MAX>[]                                          │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Maximum: 91                                                          ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
                                 Modifying Elements
                               o════════════════════o
  
  \𝑠𝑒𝑡 writes a value at a given index:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<ARR_MODIFY>[]#{                                               │
  │ 2:  │      \let<arr:int[]>{[1, 2, 3]}                                        │
  │ 3:  │      \set<arr>[1]{99}                                                  │
  │ 4:  │      \return{\at<arr>[1]}                                              │
  │ 5:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 6:  │                                                                        │
  │ 7:  │  After set: \invoke<ARR_MODIFY>[]                                      │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   After set: 99                                                        ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
                                   String Arrays
                                 o═══════════════o
  
  Arrays can also hold strings:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<STR_ARR>[]#{                                                  │
  │ 2:  │      \let<words:string[]>{[hello, world, CL]}                          │
  │ 3:  │      \return{\at<words>[2]}                                            │
  │ 4:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 5:  │                                                                        │
  │ 6:  │  Third word: \invoke<STR_ARR>[]                                        │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Third word: CL                                                       ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  String arrays use 𝑠𝑡𝑟𝑖𝑛𝑔[] as the type. Access and mutation work  identically to
  integer arrays.
  
                                  Stack Operations
                                o══════════════════o
  
  Arrays double as stacks with LIFO (last-in, first-out) semantics:
  
    ● \𝑝𝑢𝑠ℎ<arr>{value} – append to end
    ● \𝑝𝑜𝑝<arr> – remove and return the last element
    ● \𝑝𝑒𝑒𝑘<arr> – read the last element without removing
    ● \𝑙𝑒𝑛<arr> – the current depth
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \push<COLORS>{red}                                                    │
  │ 2:  │  \push<COLORS>{green}                                                  │
  │ 3:  │  \push<COLORS>{blue}                                                   │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  Peek: \peek<COLORS> \\                                                │
  │ 6:  │  Pop: \pop<COLORS>, \pop<COLORS>, \pop<COLORS> \\                      │
  │ 7:  │  Length after: \len<COLORS>                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Peek: blue                                                           ░│
     │   Pop: blue, green, red                                                ░│
     │   Length after: 0                                                      ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Popping  and peeking an empty stack  returns an empty  string. This makes stacks
  safe to drain in a loop without bounds checking.
  
                                  Queue Operations
                                o══════════════════o
  
  For FIFO (first-in, first-out) ordering, use the queue interface:
  
    ● \𝑒𝑛𝑞𝑢𝑒𝑢𝑒<arr>{value} – append to back
    ● \𝑑𝑒𝑞𝑢𝑒𝑢𝑒<arr> – remove and return from the front
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \enqueue<TASKS>{compile}                                              │
  │ 2:  │  \enqueue<TASKS>{link}                                                 │
  │ 3:  │  \enqueue<TASKS>{test}                                                 │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  Order: \dequeue<TASKS>, \dequeue<TASKS>, \dequeue<TASKS>              │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Order: compile, link, test                                           ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
            ............................................................
                                  STACK vs. QUEUE
  
            Both operate on the same underlying array. The only differe-
            nce is which end the removal draws from: \𝑝𝑜𝑝 takes from the
            back (LIFO),  \𝑑𝑒𝑞𝑢𝑒𝑢𝑒 takes from the front  (FIFO). You can
            freely  mix \𝑝𝑢𝑠ℎ with  either \𝑝𝑜𝑝 or \𝑑𝑒𝑞𝑢𝑒𝑢𝑒 on the  same
            array if your algorithm calls for it.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐌𝐚𝐩𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Maps are  Robin Hood hash tables  mapping integer  keys to integer  values. They
  provide O(1)  average-case lookup, insertion,  and deletion.  Maps are  declared
  with pipe-delimited literal syntax:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<MAP_DEMO>[]#{                                                 │
  │ 2:  │      \let<m:map>{|1->100, 2->200, 3->300|}                             │
  │ 3:  │      \return{\at<m>[2]}                                                │
  │ 4:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 5:  │                                                                        │
  │ 6:  │  Value at key 2: \invoke<MAP_DEMO>[]                                   │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Value at key 2: 200                                                  ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The operations mirror array access with additional map-specific commands:
  
    ● \𝑎𝑡<m>[key] – read the value for a key
    ● \𝑠𝑒𝑡<m>[key]{value} – write a value for a key
    ● \𝑙𝑒𝑛<m> – the number of entries
    ● \𝑚𝑎𝑝_ℎ𝑎𝑠<m>[key] – 1 if the key exists, 0 otherwise
    ● \𝑚𝑎𝑝_𝑑𝑒𝑙<m>[key] – delete a key-value pair
    ● \𝑚𝑎𝑝_𝑘𝑒𝑦𝑠<m> – all keys as a heap array
  
  An empty map is written as ||.
  
            ............................................................
                                 VERBATIM AND MAPS
  
            Map  literals use pipe  characters, which conflict  with the
            default \𝑣𝑒𝑟𝑏 delimiter. When showing map code in a verbatim
            block,        use        a       different        delimiter:
            \𝑣𝑒𝑟𝑏\textasciitilde…\textasciitilde works well.
            ............................................................
                              Membership and Deletion
                            o═════════════════════════o
  
  \𝑚𝑎𝑝_ℎ𝑎𝑠  tests whether a key exists without reading its value. \𝑚𝑎𝑝_𝑑𝑒𝑙 removes
  a key entirely:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<MAP_OPS>[]#{                                                  │
  │ 2:  │      \let<m:map>{|10->1, 20->2, 30->3|}                                │
  │ 3:  │      \let<before:int>{\map_has<m>[20]}                                 │
  │ 4:  │      \map_del<m>[20]                                                   │
  │ 5:  │      \let<after:int>{\map_has<m>[20]}                                  │
  │ 6:  │      \return{\add{\mul{${before}, 10}, ${after}}}                      │
  │ 7:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 8:  │                                                                        │
  │ 9:  │  before=1, after=0 encoded as: \invoke<MAP_OPS>[]                      │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   before=1, after=0 encoded as: 10                                     ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The  return value 10 encodes both  results: \𝑚𝑎𝑝_ℎ𝑎𝑠 returned 1 before  deletion
  and 0 after.
  
                                Iterating over a Map
                              o══════════════════════o
  
  Maps have no built-in iterator. Instead, extract the keys with  \𝑚𝑎𝑝_𝑘𝑒𝑦𝑠, which
  returns a heap-allocated array of all keys:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<MAP_SUM>[]#{                                                  │
  │ 2:  │      \let<m:map>{|1->10, 2->20, 3->30|}                                │
  │ 3:  │      \let<keys:int>{\map_keys<m>}                                      │
  │ 4:  │      \let<n:int>{\mem_len{${keys}}}                                    │
  │ 5:  │      \let<sum:int>{0}                                                  │
  │ 6:  │      \let<i:int>{0}                                                    │
  │ 7:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 8:  │          \exit_when{\ge{${i}, ${n}}}                                   │
  │ 9:  │          \let<key:int>{\mem_load{${keys}, ${i}}}                       │
  │ 10: │          \let<sum>{\add{${sum}, \at<m>[${key}]}}                       │
  │ 11: │          \inc<i>                                                       │
  │ 12: │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 13: │      \return{${sum}}                                                   │
  │ 14: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 15: │                                                                        │
  │ 16: │  Map value sum: \invoke<MAP_SUM>[]                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Map value sum: 60                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Notice that  \𝑚𝑎𝑝_𝑘𝑒𝑦𝑠 returns a ℎ𝑒𝑎𝑝  𝑎𝑑𝑑𝑟𝑒𝑠𝑠, not a regular array. This is why
  we use \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑙𝑜𝑎𝑑 to access  individual keys and \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑙𝑒𝑛 for the count. Heap me-
  mory is explained in detail in its own section below.
  
                                A Frequency Counter
                              o═════════════════════o
  
  Maps excel at counting.  Here is a frequency counter that tallies how many times
  each value appears in an array:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<FREQ>[]#{                                                     │
  │ 2:  │      \let<data:int[]>{[3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6, 5, 3, 5]}               │
  │ 3:  │      \let<freq:map>{||}                                                │
  │ 4:  │      \let<i:int>{0}                                                    │
  │ 5:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 6:  │          \exit_when{\ge{${i}, \len<data>}}                             │
  │ 7:  │          \let<val:int>{\at<data>[${i}]}                                │
  │ 8:  │          \if{\map_has<freq>[${val}]}{                                  │
  │ 9:  │              \set<freq>[${val}]{\add{\at<freq>[${val}], 1}}            │
  │ 10: │          }\else{                                                       │
  │ 11: │              \set<freq>[${val}]{1}                                     │
  │ 12: │          }                                                             │
  │ 13: │          \inc<i>                                                       │
  │ 14: │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 15: │      \return{\at<freq>[5]}                                             │
  │ 16: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 17: │                                                                        │
  │ 18: │  Count of 5: \invoke<FREQ>[]                                           │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Count of 5: 3                                                        ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The value 5 appears  three times in the input, so the count is 3. The  pattern –
  check  with  \𝑚𝑎𝑝_ℎ𝑎𝑠, then either  increment or initialize  –  is the  standard
  approach for map-based accumulators.
  
  
  𝐀𝐝𝐝𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐬 𝐏𝐚𝐬𝐬𝐢𝐧𝐠
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  By default,  collections passed to a lambda are copied. When you need a function
  to modify the caller’s array or map, pass an 𝑎𝑑𝑑𝑟𝑒𝑠𝑠 instead:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<FILL>[addr:address, n:int, val:int]#{                         │
  │ 2:  │      \let<i:int>{0}                                                    │
  │ 3:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 4:  │          \exit_when{\ge{${i}, ${n}}}                                   │
  │ 5:  │          \set<*addr>[${i}]{${val}}                                     │
  │ 6:  │          \inc<i>                                                       │
  │ 7:  │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 8:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 9:  │                                                                        │
  │ 10: │  \lambda<DEMO_ADDR>[]#{                                                │
  │ 11: │      \let<arr:int[]>{[0, 0, 0, 0, 0]}                                  │
  │ 12: │      \invoke<FILL>[\addressof<arr>, 5, 42]                             │
  │ 13: │      \return{\at<arr>[2]}                                              │
  │ 14: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 15: │                                                                        │
  │ 16: │  After fill: \invoke<DEMO_ADDR>[]                                      │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   After fill: 42                                                       ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The key pieces:
  
    ● \𝑎𝑑𝑑𝑟𝑒𝑠𝑠𝑜𝑓<name> – obtains the address of a collection
    ● \𝑎𝑡<*addr>[i] – dereferences the address to read
    ● \𝑠𝑒𝑡<*addr>[i]{v} – dereferences the address to write
  
  The  asterisk in <*addr> is the  dereference operator, analogous to C’s  pointer
  dereference.  When 𝐹𝐼𝐿𝐿 writes through  <*addr>, it modifies the original 𝑎𝑟𝑟 in
  the caller’s scope.
  
            ............................................................
                              TWO KINDS OF INDIRECTION
  
            CL supports two dereference patterns. \𝑎𝑑𝑑𝑟𝑒𝑠𝑠𝑜𝑓 gives a ha-
            ndle  to  a collection  –  suitable  for  arrays  and  maps.
            String-based  indirection  lets a string  variable hold  the
            𝑛𝑎𝑚𝑒 of another  variable:  \𝑖𝑛𝑐<*name> increments  whatever
            variable  the string names. Both use the * prefix,  but they
            operate at different levels.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐃𝐲𝐧𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐜 𝐕𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞 𝐍𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Sometimes you need to address variables whose names are  constructed at runtime.
  CL supports nested {} expressions for computed names:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<DYN_ACCESS>[]#{                                               │
  │ 2:  │      \let<item0:int>{100}                                              │
  │ 3:  │      \let<item1:int>{200}                                              │
  │ 4:  │      \let<item2:int>{300}                                              │
  │ 5:  │      \let<i:int>{1}                                                    │
  │ 6:  │      \return{${item${i}}}                                              │
  │ 7:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 8:  │                                                                        │
  │ 9:  │  Item 1: \invoke<DYN_ACCESS>[]                                         │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Item 1: 200                                                          ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The expression  ${item${i}} first evaluates the inner ${i} to get 1, then conca-
  tenates to form 𝑖𝑡𝑒𝑚1, and  finally looks up that  variable. This is essentially
  computed variable names.
  
  The pattern extends to multiple indices. A 2D grid stored in flat variables:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<GRID_2D>[]#{                                                  │
  │ 2:  │      \let<cell00:int>{11}                                              │
  │ 3:  │      \let<cell01:int>{12}                                              │
  │ 4:  │      \let<cell10:int>{21}                                              │
  │ 5:  │      \let<cell11:int>{22}                                              │
  │ 6:  │      \let<sum:int>{0}                                                  │
  │ 7:  │      \let<r:int>{0}                                                    │
  │ 8:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 9:  │          \exit_when{\ge{${r}, 2}}                                      │
  │ 10: │          \let<c:int>{0}                                                │
  │ 11: │          \begin{loop}                                                  │
  │ 12: │              \exit_when{\ge{${c}, 2}}                                  │
  │ 13: │              \let<sum>{\add{${sum}, ${cell${r}${c}}}}                  │
  │ 14: │              \inc<c>                                                   │
  │ 15: │          \end{loop}                                                    │
  │ 16: │          \inc<r>                                                       │
  │ 17: │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 18: │      \return{${sum}}                                                   │
  │ 19: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 20: │                                                                        │
  │ 21: │  Grid sum: \invoke<GRID_2D>[]                                          │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Grid sum: 66                                                         ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  ${cell${r}${c}}  resolves both indices:  when 𝑟 = 1 and 𝑐 = 0 it becomes 𝑐𝑒𝑙𝑙10,
  yielding 21.
  
                                  Dynamic Mutation
                                o══════════════════o
  
  Dynamic names also work with mutators. \inc<${slot${target}}> increments whiche-
  ver variable the index resolves to:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<DYN_INC>[]#{                                                  │
  │ 2:  │      \let<slot0:int>{0}                                                │
  │ 3:  │      \let<slot1:int>{0}                                                │
  │ 4:  │      \let<slot2:int>{0}                                                │
  │ 5:  │      \let<i:int>{0}                                                    │
  │ 6:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 7:  │          \exit_when{\ge{${i}, 30}}                                     │
  │ 8:  │          \let<target:int>{\mod{${i}, 3}}                               │
  │ 9:  │          \inc<${slot${target}}>                                        │
  │ 10: │          \inc<i>                                                       │
  │ 11: │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 12: │      \return{\add{\add{${slot0}, ${slot1}}, ${slot2}}}                 │
  │ 13: │  }                                                                     │
  │ 14: │                                                                        │
  │ 15: │  30 across 3 slots: \invoke<DYN_INC>[]                                 │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   30 across 3 slots: 30                                                ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Each iteration  increments a different slot based on 𝑖 mod 3. After 30 iteratio-
  ns, each slot holds 10, and the total is 30.
  
                              String-Based Indirection
                            o══════════════════════════o
  
  A separate  pattern uses a string variable that holds the name of another varia-
  ble. The * prefix dereferences the name:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<STR_DEREF>[]#{                                                │
  │ 2:  │      \let<counter:int>{0}                                              │
  │ 3:  │      \let<name:string>{counter}                                        │
  │ 4:  │      \inc<*name>                                                       │
  │ 5:  │      \inc<*name>                                                       │
  │ 6:  │      \inc<*name>                                                       │
  │ 7:  │      \return{${counter}}                                               │
  │ 8:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 9:  │                                                                        │
  │ 10: │  Result: \invoke<STR_DEREF>[]                                          │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Result: 3                                                            ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  \𝑖𝑛𝑐<*name> looks up the string stored in 𝑛𝑎𝑚𝑒 – which is "counter" – and incre-
  ments that variable. Three increments bring 𝑐𝑜𝑢𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑟 from 0 to 3.
  
  
  𝐇𝐞𝐚𝐩 𝐌𝐞𝐦𝐨𝐫𝐲
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  CL provides manual heap  allocation for data that needs to persist across lambda
  calls  or  that is too  large for the scope  system. The heap is a flat  address
  space of integer slots:
  
    ● \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑎𝑙𝑙𝑜𝑐{size} – allocate a block, returns an address
    ● \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑠𝑡𝑜𝑟𝑒{addr, index, value} – write to a slot
    ● \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑙𝑜𝑎𝑑{addr, index} – read from a slot
    ● \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑙𝑒𝑛{addr} – the number of slots in the block
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<HEAP_DEMO>[]#{                                                │
  │ 2:  │      \let<buf:int>{\mem_alloc{5}}                                      │
  │ 3:  │      \mem_store{${buf}, 0, 42}                                         │
  │ 4:  │      \mem_store{${buf}, 1, 99}                                         │
  │ 5:  │      \return{\add{                                                     │
  │ 6:  │          \mem_load{${buf}, 0},                                         │
  │ 7:  │          \mem_load{${buf}, 1}                                          │
  │ 8:  │      }}                                                                │
  │ 9:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 10: │                                                                        │
  │ 11: │  Heap sum: \invoke<HEAP_DEMO>[]                                        │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Heap sum: 141                                                        ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Heap blocks persist for the document’s lifetime. Once allocated, the address can
  be stored in a variable and passed between lambdas. The Matrix Digital Rain exa-
  mple later in this guide uses the heap as a virtual screen buffer – each cell is
  a packed integer holding both a character index and a color tier.
  
  You already  encountered heap memory indirectly: \𝑚𝑎𝑝_𝑘𝑒𝑦𝑠 returns a heap addre-
  ss. That is why the map  iteration pattern uses \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑙𝑜𝑎𝑑 and \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑙𝑒𝑛 to trave-
  rse the key array.
  
            ............................................................
                                  HEAP vs. ARRAYS
  
            Arrays  (\𝑙𝑒𝑡<arr:int[]>{…}) live in the  VM’s scope  system
            and are garbage-collected when their scope ends. Heap blocks
            (\𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑎𝑙𝑙𝑜𝑐) persist globally. Use arrays for local data wi-
            thin a single  lambda; use the  heap when data must  survive
            across calls or when you need to share large buffers between
            lambdas.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐎𝐮𝐭𝐩𝐮𝐭 𝐎𝐩𝐞𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Most lambdas compute and return values. But CL also supports direct terminal ou-
  tput for building interactive applications:
  
    ● \𝑒𝑚𝑖𝑡{expr} – output a value as text
    ● \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟{row, col} – move the terminal cursor (1-based)
    ● \𝑎𝑛𝑠𝑖{codes} – emit an ANSI escape sequence
  
  These commands bypass the normal  typesetting pipeline and write directly to the
  terminal. They are the foundation of real-time programs like Matrix Digital Rain
  and Game of Life.
  
                                  ANSI Color Codes
                                o══════════════════o
  
  \𝑎𝑛𝑠𝑖 accepts standard ANSI SGR codes:
  
    ┌────────────────────────┬───────────────────────┐
    │ Code                   │ Effect                │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ 0                      │ Reset all attributes  │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ 1                      │ Bold                  │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ 3                      │ Italic                │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ 4                      │ Underline             │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ 31–37                  │ Foreground     colors │
    │                        │ (red..white)          │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ 90–97                  │ Bright foreground co- │
    │                        │ lors                  │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ 40–47                  │ Background colors     │
    └────────────────────────┴───────────────────────┘
  
  Multiple  codes can be combined with semicolons:  \𝑎𝑛𝑠𝑖{92;40} sets bright green
  foreground on black background.
  
  The stdlib also provides friendlier wrappers:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \term_fg[red]{text}                                                   │
  │ 2:  │  \term_bg[blue]{text}                                                  │
  │ 3:  │  \term_color[fg=white,bg=red]{text}                                    │
  │ 4:  │  \term_bold{text}                                                      │
  │ 5:  │  \term_underline{text}                                                 │
  │ 6:  │  \term_inverse{text}                                                   │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                   Cursor Control
                                 o════════════════o
  
  Beyond \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟{row, col}, a full suite of positioning commands is available:
  
    ┌────────────────────────┬───────────────────────┐
    │ Command                │ Effect                │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟_𝑢𝑝{n}          │ Move up n lines       │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟_𝑑𝑜𝑤𝑛{n}        │ Move down n lines     │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟_𝑙𝑒𝑓𝑡{n}        │ Move left n columns   │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟_𝑟𝑖𝑔ℎ𝑡{n}       │ Move right n columns  │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟_𝑠𝑎𝑣𝑒           │ Save cursor position  │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟_𝑟𝑒𝑠𝑡𝑜𝑟𝑒        │ Restore  saved  posi- │
    │                        │ tion                  │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟_ℎ𝑖𝑑𝑒         / │ Toggle cursor visibi- │
    │ \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟_𝑠ℎ𝑜𝑤           │ lity                  │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑐𝑙𝑒𝑎𝑟_𝑠𝑐𝑟𝑒𝑒𝑛          │ Clear entire screen   │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑐𝑙𝑒𝑎𝑟_𝑙𝑖𝑛𝑒          / │ Clear  current line / │
    │ \𝑐𝑙𝑒𝑎𝑟_𝑡𝑜_𝑒𝑜𝑙          │ to end                │
    ╞════════════════════════╪═══════════════════════╡
    │ \𝑡𝑒𝑟𝑚_𝑟𝑜𝑤𝑠           / │ Terminal dimensions   │
    │ \𝑡𝑒𝑟𝑚_𝑐𝑜𝑙𝑠             │                       │
    └────────────────────────┴───────────────────────┘
  
  
  𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐌𝐚𝐢𝐧 𝐋𝐨𝐨𝐩
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Interactive  programs  use  \𝑚𝑎𝑖𝑛{body}. This puts  the terminal into  alternate
  screen mode and runs the body in an infinite  loop, clearing the screen  between
  frames:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \main{                                                                │
  │ 2:  │      % Process input                                                   │
  │ 3:  │      \if{\haskey}{                                                     │
  │ 4:  │          \let<k>{\getkey}                                              │
  │ 5:  │          \if{\streq{${k},q}}{\exit}                                    │
  │ 6:  │      }                                                                 │
  │ 7:  │      % Compute                                                         │
  │ 8:  │      \invoke<UPDATE>[...]                                              │
  │ 9:  │      % Render                                                          │
  │ 10: │      \invoke<DRAW>[...]                                                │
  │ 11: │      \wait{30}   % ~33 fps                                             │
  │ 12: │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The  architecture is always: read input, compute the next state, render the fra-
  me, sleep. Input commands include:
  
    ● \ℎ𝑎𝑠𝑘𝑒𝑦 – 1 if a keypress is waiting
    ● \𝑔𝑒𝑡𝑘𝑒𝑦 – consume and return the next key
    ● \𝑔𝑒𝑡𝑚𝑜𝑢𝑠𝑒𝑋, \𝑔𝑒𝑡𝑚𝑜𝑢𝑠𝑒𝑌 – mouse position
    ● \𝑔𝑒𝑡𝑚𝑜𝑢𝑠𝑒𝑏𝑢𝑡𝑡𝑜𝑛 – mouse button state (1=left, 3=right)
    ● \𝑒𝑥𝑖𝑡 – quit the program
    ● \𝑤𝑎𝑖𝑡{ms} – pause for milliseconds
  
  The \𝑚𝑎𝑖𝑛 loop manages the terminal lifecycle automatically: it enters alternate
  screen mode,  enables raw  input, and  restores the  terminal on exit.  You just
  write the frame logic.
  
            ............................................................
                          CURSOR POSITIONING WITHOUT MAIN
  
            You do not need  \𝑚𝑎𝑖𝑛 for simple cursor  tricks. The cursor
            commands work in regular documents too – useful for progress
            bars or status updates that overwrite themselves in place.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐩𝐫𝐞𝐭𝐞𝐫/𝐂𝐋 𝐁𝐫𝐢𝐝𝐠𝐞
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Programs do not  have to be pure CL. The most  powerful pattern in Hyades is mi-
  xing the text  interpreter with compiled  lambdas – letting each do what it does
  best. The interpreter handles  initialization, configuration,  and string proce-
  ssing. CL handles  computation-heavy inner loops. The bridge between them is the
  𝑝𝑒𝑟𝑠𝑖𝑠𝑡𝑒𝑛𝑡 𝑠𝑡𝑜𝑟𝑒: heap blocks, maps, and arrays that both sides can access.
  
                          Allocating from the Interpreter
                        o═════════════════════════════════o
  
  Heap memory and maps can only be 𝑐𝑟𝑒𝑎𝑡𝑒𝑑 inside a #{} block (they are  Subnivean
  operations).  But you can wrap the  allocation in a tiny lambda and call it from
  the interpreter:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  %%% Create a helper lambda that allocates and returns a heap address  │
  │ 2:  │  \lambda<ALLOC>[size:int]#{\return{\mem_alloc{${size}}}}               │
  │ 3:  │                                                                        │
  │ 4:  │  %%% Interpreter allocates a buffer through the helper                 │
  │ 5:  │  \let<buf>{\invoke<ALLOC>[\mul{${COLS}, ${ROWS}}]}                     │
  │ 6:  │                                                                        │
  │ 7:  │  %%% Maps are allocated with pipe literals inside #{}                  │
  │ 8:  │  \let<pos_map>#{||}                                                    │
  │ 9:  │  \let<spd_map>#{||}                                                    │
  │ 10: │                                                                        │
  │ 11: │  %%% Arrays can be allocated directly with data                        │
  │ 12: │  \let<grid>#{[0,0,1,0,0,1,1,1,0]}                                      │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  After  these  lines, ${buf},  ${pos_map}, ${spd_map}, and  ${grid} are  ordinary
  integer addresses that the  interpreter can store, pass, and hand to CL lambdas.
  The array form is especially  convenient – the non-sparse Game of Life uses \le-
  t<grid>#{[0,0,1,...]} to create its initial board directly from the interpreter,
  yielding a heap  array that  CL  lambdas  can read  and write via  \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑙𝑜𝑎𝑑 and
  \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑠𝑡𝑜𝑟𝑒.
  
                         Initialization in the Interpreter
                       o═══════════════════════════════════o
  
  The  interpreter is often more  convenient for  setup code. Matrix  Digital Rain
  initializes its column state with a simple loop in interpreter mode:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  %%% Initialize columns with random starting positions                 │
  │ 2:  │  \let<c>{0}                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  \begin{loop}                                                          │
  │ 4:  │      \exit_when{\ge{${c}, ${COLS}}}                                    │
  │ 5:  │      \map_set<pos_map>{${c}, \sub{0, \rand{${ROWS}}}}                  │
  │ 6:  │      \map_set<spd_map>{${c}, \add{1, \rand{3}}}                        │
  │ 7:  │      \map_set<trail_map>{${c}, \add{8, \rand{24}}}                     │
  │ 8:  │      \inc<c>                                                           │
  │ 9:  │  \end{loop}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  This loop runs in the text interpreter – no #{}, no type  annotations. It writes
  directly into the persistent maps using \𝑚𝑎𝑝_𝑠𝑒𝑡. Those same maps are later read
  by the compiled COMPUTE lambda through address dereferences (\at<*addr>[key]).
  
                         Passing State Across the Boundary
                       o═══════════════════════════════════o
  
  The main loop ties everything together by passing  persistent-store addresses as
  lambda parameters:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \main{                                                                │
  │ 2:  │      \invoke<COMPUTE>[${COLS}, ${ROWS}, ${frame},                      │
  │ 3:  │          ${buf}, ${pos_map}, ${spd_map},                               │
  │ 4:  │          ${trail_map}, ${chr_map}]                                     │
  │ 5:  │      \invoke<RENDER>[${COLS}, ${ROWS}, ${buf}, ${K}]                   │
  │ 6:  │      \inc<frame>                                                       │
  │ 7:  │      \wait{60}                                                         │
  │ 8:  │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The interpreter owns the addresses; the CL lambdas receive them as plain intege-
  rs. Inside the lambda,  \at<*addr>[key] reads through  the address and  \set<*a-
  ddr>[key]{val}  writes back.  Because both sides  reference the same  persistent
  store, changes made by COMPUTE are  instantly visible to RENDER – no copying re-
  quired.
  
                                 External Callbacks
                               o════════════════════o
  
  How does this work under the hood? When a CL lambda dereferences an address, the
  Subnivean VM uses 𝑒𝑥𝑡𝑒𝑟𝑛𝑎𝑙 𝑐𝑎𝑙𝑙𝑏𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑠 to reach into the interpreter:
  
    ● 𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐚𝐲_𝐥𝐨𝐨𝐤𝐮𝐩: fetches an array by name from the interpreter’s scope
    ● 𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐚𝐲_𝐬𝐞𝐭: writes an element to an interpreter-owned array
    ● 𝐥𝐚𝐦𝐛𝐝𝐚_𝐜𝐨𝐦𝐩𝐢𝐥𝐞: compiles another lambda on demand when first referenced
  
  These callbacks fire transparently. When a CL lambda calls \invoke<OTHER_LAMBDA-
  >[...] and  OTHER_LAMBDA has not yet been compiled, the VM asks the  interpreter
  to compile it, caches the result, and calls it at bytecode speed from then on.
  
            ............................................................
                               THE DESIGN PHILOSOPHY
  
            The  interpreter/CL split mirrors how CPU and GPU  cooperate
            in graphics programming: the CPU (interpreter) sets up state
            and  issues  commands; the GPU  (Subnivean VM) executes  the
            heavy  parallel work. You  don’t compile your  configuration
            files  to  SPIR-V;  you don’t  write your  physics engine in
            shell script. Use each tool where it shines.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐒𝐮𝐛𝐧𝐢𝐯𝐞𝐚𝐧 𝐕𝐢𝐫𝐭𝐮𝐚𝐥 𝐌𝐚𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐧𝐞
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Every #{} body is compiled to bytecode and executed by the Subnivean VM – a sta-
  ck-based virtual machine designed for mutable cells, lexical scopes, and closure
  semantics.  Understanding Subnivean is not  required for writing CL, but knowing
  what  happens behind the scenes helps explain why CL is fast and why certain pa-
  tterns perform better than others.
  
                                     Why a VM?
                                   o═══════════o
  
  The text  interpreter processes macros by string  expansion: each \𝑣𝑎𝑙𝑢𝑒𝑜𝑓  call
  generates text, that text is spliced into the document, and the result is re-pa-
  rsed. This is elegant for typesetting but catastrophically slow for computation.
  A simple loop running 10{,}000 iterations generates and parses 10{,}000 strings.
  
  Subnivean  bypasses text entirely.  The compiler  parses CL syntax  into an AST,
  translates  that AST into bytecode, and the VM executes the bytecode with a sta-
  ck, scope chain, and  register-like cells. There is no string generation, no re-
  -parsing, no macro expansion overhead.
  
  The result is a 𝟔𝟓× 𝐬𝐩𝐞𝐞𝐝𝐮𝐩. Conway’s Game of Life on a 5×5 grid for 1000 itera-
  tions:
  
    ┌───────────────────┬──────────────────┐
    │ Engine            │             Time │
    ╞═══════════════════╪══════════════════╡
    │ Text interpreter  │            7.63s │
    ╞═══════════════════╪══════════════════╡
    │ Subnivean VM      │           0.118s │
    └───────────────────┴──────────────────┘
  
  This is what makes interactive  applications possible. Without Subnivean, Matrix
  Digital Rain could not maintain a usable frame rate.
  
                              The Compilation Pipeline
                            o══════════════════════════o
  
  When Hyades encounters #{…}, it:
  
    ● Parses the CL syntax into an abstract syntax tree (AST)
    ● Compiles the AST to Subnivean bytecode instructions
    ● Stores the bytecode in a function object
    ● On each \𝑖𝑛𝑣𝑜𝑘𝑒, the VM executes the bytecode directly
  
  The  compilation happens once at definition  time. Subsequent calls run the pre-
  -compiled bytecode with zero parsing overhead. This is analogous to how an ahea-
  d-of-time compiler works.
  
                                The Execution Model
                              o═════════════════════o
  
  The VM maintains five components:
  
    ● A 𝐯𝐚𝐥𝐮𝐞 𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐜𝐤 for operand computation
    ● A 𝐜𝐚𝐥𝐥 𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐜𝐤 for function activation records
    ● A 𝐬𝐜𝐨𝐩𝐞 𝐜𝐡𝐚𝐢𝐧 for lexical variable resolution
    ● A 𝐬𝐲𝐦𝐛𝐨𝐥 𝐭𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞 for interned identifiers
    ● An 𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐩𝐮𝐭 𝐛𝐮𝐟𝐟𝐞𝐫 for \𝑒𝑚𝑖𝑡 results
  
  Variables  in  CL are  stored in 𝑐𝑒𝑙𝑙𝑠 – mutable  boxes that  live in the  scope
  chain.  When  you write  \𝑙𝑒𝑡<x:int>{5}, the compiler  emits: push the  value 5,
  create a new cell  containing it, and bind the cell to the symbol “x” in the cu-
  rrent  scope.  When you  write {x},  it  emits:  look up the cell  bound to “x”,
  extract its value. Mutation  (\𝑖𝑛𝑐<x>) finds the cell and modifies it in place –
  no allocation, no copying.
  
                             Closures and Scope Capture
                           o════════════════════════════o
  
  Closures  capture the scope at definition  time. A lambda  defined inside a loop
  captures the  per-iteration scope, which means each closure gets its own copy of
  the loop  variable. This is the same  semantics as modern  JavaScript’s 𝑙𝑒𝑡 in a
  for loop – each  iteration creates a fresh scope, and each closure  captures its
  own version.
  
                                 External Callbacks
                               o════════════════════o
  
  The VM communicates  with the host Hyades  interpreter through three  callbacks:
  array lookup, array write, and lambda compilation. When CL code references a va-
  riable  that  does  not  exist  in  the  VM’s  scope,  the  callback checks  the
  interpreter’s  variable store. This is how lambdas access  document-level varia-
  bles – counters,  arrays, and maps defined outside any #{} block are  transpare-
  ntly available inside it.
  
            ............................................................
                               PERFORMANCE: INLINING
  
            Function calls in Subnivean  have overhead: scope  creation,
            argument  copying, stack frame setup. In tight inner loops –
            thousands of iterations  per frame – this  adds up. Both the
            Game of Life and Matrix Digital Rain inline their inner-loop
            logic rather than  calling helper lambdas. When  performance
            matters, prefer one large lambda over many small ones in hot
            paths.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐒𝐭𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐚𝐫𝐝 𝐋𝐢𝐛𝐫𝐚𝐫𝐲 𝐅𝐮𝐧𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  The  standard  library includes  pre-built CL functions in the STD::  namespace.
  These cover common patterns so you do not have to write them yourself:
  
                                  Array Generators
                                o══════════════════o
    ● STD::RANGE[start, end] – integers from start to end-1
    ● STD::IOTA[n] – integers from 0 to n-1
    ● STD::REPEAT[n, val] – n copies of a value
                                     Aggregates
                                   o════════════o
    ● STD::SUM, STD::PRODUCT – reduce an array
    ● STD::MIN, STD::MAX, STD::AVG – statistics
    ● STD::LEN, STD::COUNT – count elements
                                  Transformations
                                o═════════════════o
    ● STD::REVERSE, STD::MAP, STD::FILTER
    ● STD::TAKE, STD::DROP, STD::SLICE
    ● STD::SORT, STD::SORT_DESC, STD::JOIN
                                   Math Utilities
                                 o════════════════o
    ● STD::ABS, STD::SIGN, STD::CLAMP
    ● STD::POW, STD::FACTORIAL, STD::GCD, STD::LCM, STD::FIB
                                     Formatting
                                   o════════════o
    ● STD::ORDINAL – 1 \textrightarrow “1st”, 2 \textrightarrow “2nd”
    ● STD::ROMAN – 42 \textrightarrow “XLII”
                                     Predicates
                                   o════════════o
    ● STD::IS_POSITIVE, STD::IS_NEGATIVE, STD::IS_ZERO
    ● STD::IS_EVEN, STD::IS_ODD
  
  
  𝐈𝐧 𝐏𝐫𝐚𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐜𝐞: 𝐆𝐚𝐦𝐞 𝐨𝐟 𝐋𝐢𝐟𝐞
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Conway’s Game of Life is the  canonical test of a computational  system’s expre-
  ssiveness.  The rules are  simple: cells on a grid are either alive or dead, and
  their fate  depends on how many  neighbors they have. With just these rules, the
  system is Turing-complete – capable of universal computation.
  
  The Hyades implementation uses a 𝑠𝑝𝑎𝑟𝑠𝑒  representation. Instead of allocating a
  huge 2D array,  only live cells are stored in a map. The key is an encoded  coo-
  rdinate: row × 10000 + column.
  
                                Encoding Coordinates
                              o══════════════════════o
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<ENCODE_KEY>[row:int, col:int]#{                               │
  │ 2:  │      \return{\add{\mul{${row}, 10000}, ${col}}}                        │
  │ 3:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  \lambda<DECODE_ROW>[key:int]#{                                        │
  │ 6:  │      \return{\div{${key}, 10000}}                                      │
  │ 7:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 8:  │                                                                        │
  │ 9:  │  \lambda<DECODE_COL>[key:int]#{                                        │
  │ 10: │      \return{\mod{${key}, 10000}}                                      │
  │ 11: │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  A glider – the simplest moving pattern – is initialized as five map entries:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<grid>#{|10002->1, 20003->1, 30001->1, 30002->1, 30003->1|}       │
  │ 2:  │  \let<temp>#{||}                                                       │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                 The Step Function
                               o═══════════════════o
  
  The simulation step is the heart of the program. It works in three phases:
  
    ● 𝐁𝐮𝐢𝐥𝐝 𝐜𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐝𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐬: gather all live cells and their neighbors into a set. Only
      these cells can change state.
    ● 𝐄𝐯𝐚𝐥𝐮𝐚𝐭𝐞: for each candidate, count its live neighbors and apply the rules
      (survive with 2–3 neighbors, birth with exactly 3).
    ● 𝐒𝐰𝐚𝐩: clear the current grid and copy the results from a temporary map.
  
  The neighbor-counting loop iterates the 3×3 neighborhood with toroidal wrapping:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  %%% Count neighbors (inlined for performance)                         │
  │ 2:  │  \let<count:int>{0}                                                    │
  │ 3:  │  \let<dr:int>{-1}                                                      │
  │ 4:  │  \begin{loop}                                                          │
  │ 5:  │      \exit_when{\gt{${dr}, 1}}                                         │
  │ 6:  │      \let<dc:int>{-1}                                                  │
  │ 7:  │      \begin{loop}                                                      │
  │ 8:  │          \exit_when{\gt{${dc}, 1}}                                     │
  │ 9:  │          \if{\and{\eq{${dr}, 0}, \eq{${dc}, 0}}}{}                     │
  │ 10: │          \else{                                                        │
  │ 11: │              \let<nr:int>{\mod{\add{\add{${row}, ${dr}},               │
  │ 12: │                  ${height}}, ${height}}}                               │
  │ 13: │              \let<nc:int>{\mod{\add{\add{${col}, ${dc}},               │
  │ 14: │                  ${width}}, ${width}}}                                 │
  │ 15: │              \let<nkey:int>{\add{\mul{${nr}, 10000}, ${nc}}}           │
  │ 16: │              \if{\map_has{${grid_map}, ${nkey}}}{\inc<count>}          │
  │ 17: │          }                                                             │
  │ 18: │          \inc<dc>                                                      │
  │ 19: │      \end{loop}                                                        │
  │ 20: │      \inc<dr>                                                          │
  │ 21: │  \end{loop}                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The double \𝑚𝑜𝑑 with the added  height/width ensures coordinates wrap around the
  grid  edges – a standard torus  topology. The \𝑚𝑎𝑝_ℎ𝑎𝑠  check is O(1)  thanks to
  Robin Hood hashing.
  
                                The Next-State Rule
                              o═════════════════════o
  
  The Game of Life rule fits in a single conditional:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<next:int>{                                                       │
  │ 2:  │      \if{${current}}{                                                  │
  │ 3:  │          \if{\or{\eq{${count}, 2},                                     │
  │ 4:  │                  \eq{${count}, 3}}}{1}                                 │
  │ 5:  │          \else{0}                                                      │
  │ 6:  │      }\else{                                                           │
  │ 7:  │          \if{\eq{${count}, 3}}{1}                                      │
  │ 8:  │          \else{0}                                                      │
  │ 9:  │      }                                                                 │
  │ 10: │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  If a cell is alive, it survives  with 2 or 3 neighbors. If dead, it is born with
  exactly 3. Everything else dies or stays dead.
  
                                     Rendering
                                   o═══════════o
  
  Each frame, the display lambda  iterates every visible  cell, queries the sparse
  map, and emits a colored block character:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \if{${is_hover}}{                                                     │
  │ 2:  │      \if{${alive}}{\ansi{93}\emit{block}\ansi{0}}                      │
  │ 3:  │      \else{\ansi{43;30}\emit{block}\ansi{0}}                           │
  │ 4:  │  }\else{                                                               │
  │ 5:  │      \if{${alive}}{\ansi{92}\emit{block}\ansi{0}}                      │
  │ 6:  │      \else{\ansi{90}\emit{block}\ansi{0}}                              │
  │ 7:  │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  Alive cells are  green; dead cells are dim gray; the cell under the mouse cursor
  is highlighted in yellow. The full  implementation supports pausing, mouse inte-
  raction for toggling cells, and runs at 30+ fps on a standard terminal.
  
            ............................................................
                                TURING COMPLETENESS
  
            The  Game of Life is famously  Turing-complete: any computa-
            tion that a Turing machine can perform, a sufficiently large
            Life grid can also  perform. The fact that Hyades can imple-
            ment Life in CL – with maps, loops, functions, and conditio-
            nals – demonstrates  that CL itself  has  the  computational
            power to express arbitrary algorithms.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐈𝐧 𝐏𝐫𝐚𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐜𝐞: 𝐌𝐚𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐱 𝐃𝐢𝐠𝐢𝐭𝐚𝐥 𝐑𝐚𝐢𝐧
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  The Matrix Digital Rain is a more visually ambitious example. It renders falling
  columns of Katakana  characters in green,  mimicking the iconic  effect from the
  film. This program exercises nearly every CL feature: arrays, maps, heap memory,
  address passing, ANSI colors, and cursor positioning.
  
                                    Architecture
                                  o══════════════o
  
  The program splits into two compiled lambdas:
  
    ● 𝐂𝐎𝐌𝐏𝐔𝐓𝐄: runs the physics simulation. For each column, it calculates which
      cells should be lit and at what brightness, writing packed values into a
      heap buffer.
    ● 𝐑𝐄𝐍𝐃𝐄𝐑: reads the heap buffer and emits ANSI-colored Katakana characters at
      the correct screen positions.
  
  This separation keeps computation pure and rendering straightforward.
  
                             The Virtual Screen Buffer
                           o═══════════════════════════o
  
  Rather than  emitting characters during  computation (which would mix logic with
  output), the program allocates a heap buffer sized to the terminal:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<ALLOC_BUF>[size:int]#{                                        │
  │ 2:  │      \return{\mem_alloc{${size}}}                                      │
  │ 3:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  \let<buf>{\invoke<ALLOC_BUF>[\mul{${COLS},${ROWS}}]}                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  Each  cell in the  buffer stores a packed integer:  𝑐ℎ𝑎𝑟_𝑖𝑛𝑑𝑒𝑥 × 4 + 𝑐𝑜𝑙𝑜𝑟_𝑡𝑖𝑒𝑟.
  The COMPUTE lambda writes these packed values; the RENDER lambda unpacks them.
  
                                 The Compute Lambda
                               o════════════════════o
  
  COMPUTE takes eight parameters – all by address so it can modify the shared sta-
  te:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \lambda<COMPUTE>[cols:int, rows:int, frm:int,                         │
  │ 2:  │      buf_addr:int, pos_addr:int, spd_addr:int,                         │
  │ 3:  │      trail_addr:int, chr_addr:int]#{                                   │
  │ 4:  │      ...                                                               │
  │ 5:  │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  For each column, it:
  
    ● Reads the current drop position and trail length from maps
    ● Iterates the trail cells, calculating a color tier (bright white head
      \textrightarrow bright green \textrightarrow dark green \textrightarrow dim
      gray tail)
    ● Picks a pseudo-random Katakana character for each cell
    ● Packs the character index and color into a single integer
    ● Writes the packed value into the heap buffer
    ● Advances the drop position and resets when it scrolls off-screen
  
  The  key  technique  is  𝑏𝑖𝑡-𝑝𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑖𝑛𝑔: a single  integer encodes two  values. The
  RENDER side unpacks with division and modulo:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<ch:int>{\div{${packed}, 4}}                                      │
  │ 2:  │  \let<clr:int>{\mod{${packed}, 4}}                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                 The Render Lambda
                               o═══════════════════o
  
  RENDER  reads the heap buffer and emits only  non-zero cells. For each lit cell,
  it positions  the cursor, selects the ANSI color, and emits the  Katakana chara-
  cter by indexing into a string array:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \if{\eq{${clr}, 0}}{\ansi{97;40}}       % bright white head           │
  │ 2:  │  \else{\if{\eq{${clr}, 1}}{\ansi{92;40}} % bright green                │
  │ 3:  │  \else{\if{\eq{${clr}, 2}}{\ansi{32;40}} % dark green                  │
  │ 4:  │  \else{\ansi{90;40}}}}                    % dim gray                   │
  │ 5:  │  \emit{\at<*k_addr>[${ch}]}                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The  <*k_addr>  dereference reads  from the  Katakana array  that was  passed by
  address from the main loop.
  
                                   The Main Loop
                                 o═══════════════o
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \main{                                                                │
  │ 2:  │      \if{\haskey}{\let<k>{\getkey}                                     │
  │ 3:  │          \if{\streq{${k},q}}{\exit}                                    │
  │ 4:  │          \if{\streq{${k},Q}}{\exit}}                                   │
  │ 5:  │      \invoke<COMPUTE>[${COLS},${ROWS},${frame},                        │
  │ 6:  │          ${buf},${pos_map},${spd_map},                                 │
  │ 7:  │          ${trail_map},${chr_map}]                                      │
  │ 8:  │      \invoke<RENDER>[${COLS},${ROWS},${buf},${K}]                      │
  │ 9:  │      \inc<frame>                                                       │
  │ 10: │      \wait{60}                                                         │
  │ 11: │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  Each frame: check for quit, run the  physics, draw the result, sleep 60 millise-
  conds. Maps  (positions, speeds, trail lengths,  character seeds) are  passed by
  address to COMPUTE, which updates them in place.
  
            ............................................................
                                  BUFFER STRATEGY
  
            The  heap  buffer acts as a “virtual  framebuffer” – COMPUTE
            writes  packed  cell  data,  RENDER reads  it. This  pattern
            avoids  interleaving  computation with  terminal I/O,  which
            would be both  slower and harder to reason about. The buffer
            also enables selective  rendering: only non-zero  cells emit
            characters, so empty space costs nothing.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐍𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐯𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  CL follows a consistent naming scheme:
  
    ┌─────────────────┬─────────────────┬─────────────────┐
    │ Category        │ Convention      │ Example         │
    ╞═════════════════╪═════════════════╪═════════════════╡
    │ Multi-word  co- │ snake_case      │ \𝑒𝑥𝑖𝑡_𝑤ℎ𝑒𝑛,     │
    │ mmands          │                 │ \𝑚𝑎𝑝_ℎ𝑎𝑠        │
    ╞═════════════════╪═════════════════╪═════════════════╡
    │ Single-word co- │ lowercase       │ \𝑙𝑒𝑡, \𝑎𝑡, \𝑠𝑒𝑡 │
    │ mmands          │                 │                 │
    ╞═════════════════╪═════════════════╪═════════════════╡
    │ User     lambda │ UPPER_CASE      │ COMPUTE, GCD    │
    │ names           │                 │                 │
    ╞═════════════════╪═════════════════╪═════════════════╡
    │ User  local va- │ lower_case      │ count, row, i   │
    │ riables         │                 │                 │
    └─────────────────┴─────────────────┴─────────────────┘
  
  Uppercase  names are global – they  persist between lambda calls and are visible
  everywhere.  Lowercase names are  local – they exist only within their  lambda’s
  scope and are freed when the call returns.
  
  This is the same convention as the macro system, and for the same reason: Hyades
  uses casing to determine scope without requiring explicit scope annotations.
  
  
  𝐐𝐮𝐢𝐜𝐤 𝐑𝐞𝐟𝐞𝐫𝐞𝐧𝐜𝐞
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    ┌───────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┐
    │ Command                           │ Description                    │
    ╞═══════════════════════════════════╪════════════════════════════════╡
    │ 𝐷𝑒𝑓𝑖𝑛𝑖𝑡𝑖𝑜𝑛𝑠 & 𝐶𝑎𝑙𝑙𝑠               │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑙𝑎𝑚𝑏𝑑𝑎<name>[p:type]#{body}      │ Define a compiled function     │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑖𝑛𝑣𝑜𝑘𝑒<name>[args]               │ Call a lambda                  │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑟𝑒𝑡𝑢𝑟𝑛{value}                    │ Return from a lambda           │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ 𝑉𝑎𝑟𝑖𝑎𝑏𝑙𝑒𝑠                         │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑙𝑒𝑡<name:type>{value}            │ Declare a typed variable       │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ {name}                            │ Read a variable                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑖𝑛𝑐<x> / \𝑑𝑒𝑐<x>                 │ Increment / decrement          │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ 𝐴𝑟𝑖𝑡ℎ𝑚𝑒𝑡𝑖𝑐                        │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑎𝑑𝑑 \𝑠𝑢𝑏 \𝑚𝑢𝑙 \𝑑𝑖𝑣 \𝑚𝑜𝑑          │ Basic arithmetic               │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑛𝑒𝑔{a}                           │ Negation                       │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑚𝑎𝑥{a,b} / \𝑚𝑖𝑛{a,b}             │ Maximum / minimum              │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑟𝑎𝑛𝑑{n}                          │ Random integer in [0, n)       │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ 𝐶𝑜𝑚𝑝𝑎𝑟𝑖𝑠𝑜𝑛𝑠 & 𝐿𝑜𝑔𝑖𝑐               │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑒𝑞 \𝑛𝑒 \𝑙𝑡 \𝑙𝑒 \𝑔𝑡 \𝑔𝑒           │ Comparisons (return 0/1)       │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑎𝑛𝑑{a,b} / \𝑜𝑟{a,b} / \𝑛𝑜𝑡{a}    │ Logic operators                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ 𝐶𝑜𝑛𝑡𝑟𝑜𝑙 𝐹𝑙𝑜𝑤                      │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑖𝑓{cond}{then}\𝑒𝑙𝑠𝑒{else}        │ Conditional                    │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛{loop}…\𝑒𝑛𝑑{loop}           │ Loop                           │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑒𝑥𝑖𝑡_𝑤ℎ𝑒𝑛{condition}             │ Break from loop                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ 𝐶𝑜𝑙𝑙𝑒𝑐𝑡𝑖𝑜𝑛𝑠                       │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑎𝑡<arr>[i] / \𝑠𝑒𝑡<arr>[i]{v}     │ Array/map read/write           │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑙𝑒𝑛<arr>                         │ Collection length              │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑚𝑎𝑝_ℎ𝑎𝑠<m>[k]                    │ Map membership test            │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑚𝑎𝑝_𝑑𝑒𝑙<m>[k]                    │ Delete map entry               │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑚𝑎𝑝_𝑘𝑒𝑦𝑠<m>                      │ All keys (heap array)          │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑝𝑢𝑠ℎ<arr>{v} / \𝑝𝑜𝑝<arr>         │ Stack (LIFO) push/pop          │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑝𝑒𝑒𝑘<arr>                        │ Read top without removing      │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑒𝑛𝑞𝑢𝑒𝑢𝑒<arr>{v} / \𝑑𝑒𝑞𝑢𝑒𝑢𝑒<arr>  │ Queue (FIFO) add/remove        │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ 𝐴𝑑𝑑𝑟𝑒𝑠𝑠 𝑃𝑎𝑠𝑠𝑖𝑛𝑔                   │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑎𝑑𝑑𝑟𝑒𝑠𝑠𝑜𝑓<name>                  │ Get collection address         │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑎𝑡<*a>[i] / \𝑠𝑒𝑡<*a>[i]{v}       │ Dereference read/write         │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ 𝐻𝑒𝑎𝑝 𝑀𝑒𝑚𝑜𝑟𝑦                       │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑎𝑙𝑙𝑜𝑐{n}                     │ Allocate heap block            │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑙𝑜𝑎𝑑{addr, i}                │ Read from heap                 │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑠𝑡𝑜𝑟𝑒{addr, i, v}            │ Write to heap                  │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑚𝑒𝑚_𝑙𝑒𝑛{addr}                    │ Heap block length              │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ 𝑇𝑒𝑟𝑚𝑖𝑛𝑎𝑙 𝑂𝑢𝑡𝑝𝑢𝑡                   │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑒𝑚𝑖𝑡{text}                       │ Output a value                 │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑟{row, col}                 │ Position cursor                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑎𝑛𝑠𝑖{codes}                      │ ANSI escape sequence           │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑚𝑎𝑖𝑛{body}                       │ Interactive main loop          │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ 𝐷𝑦𝑛𝑎𝑚𝑖𝑐 𝑁𝑎𝑚𝑒𝑠                     │                                │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ ${prefix${i}suffix}               │ Computed variable name         │
    ├───────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
    │ \𝑖𝑛𝑐<*name>                       │ String-based indirection       │
    └───────────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────┘

@label cl_guide
    Hyades has two programmability systems. The first -- macros -- is a text
    substitution engine, the subject of a separate guide. The second is
    Computational Lambdas (CL), a fully typed computational layer compiled to
    bytecode and executed by the Subnivean virtual machine. Where macros
    transform text, CL computes values: integers, strings, arrays, hash maps,
    heap memory, and terminal output fast enough for interactive applications.

    This guide builds progressively from a first lambda to complete programs.
    By the end you will understand every feature CL offers -- and you will
    have seen it drive Conway's Game of Life and a Matrix Digital Rain, both
    running live inside a typesetting engine.

    The sections build on each other, so reading front to back is recommended.
    A Quick Reference table at the end covers every command in one place.


    \section{\textbf{Your First Lambda}}

    A \textit{lambda} is a named function. The simplest form takes no
    parameters and returns a constant:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<greet>#{
    \return{42}
}

Result: \invoke<greet>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<greet>#{
        \return{42}
    }
    \indented{
        Result: \invoke<greet>[]
    }
}

    Three things to notice. First, the \# before the opening brace -- it
    tells Hyades to compile this body to Subnivean bytecode instead of
    interpreting it as text. Second, \cmd{return} provides the value that
    flows back to the call site. Third, \cmd{invoke}\<name\>[args] is the
    calling convention: the name goes in angle brackets, arguments in square
    brackets (empty here because \textit{greet} takes none).

    Without the \#, the body would be treated as a macro -- text substitution,
    not computation. The \# is the gateway to everything in this guide.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{TWO KINDS OF LAMBDA}
    A lambda body in plain braces \{...\} is interpreted as text by the
    macro engine. A lambda body in \#\{...\} is compiled to bytecode by
    Subnivean. Both are defined with \cmd{lambda}, but they live in
    different worlds. This guide covers \#\{\} exclusively.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Functions with Parameters}}

    Lambdas accept typed parameters in square brackets:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<ADD>[a:int, b:int]#{
    \return{\add{${a}, ${b}}}
}

\invoke<ADD>[3, 4] \\
\invoke<ADD>[100, 200]
|}{%
    \lambda<ADD>[a:int, b:int]#{
        \return{\add{${a}, ${b}}}
    }
    \indented{
        \invoke<ADD>[3, 4] \\
        \invoke<ADD>[100, 200]
    }
}

    Each parameter carries a type annotation: \textit{a:int} declares a
    parameter named \textit{a} of type \textit{int}. The available types
    are covered in the next section.

    Functions can call other functions. Because each lambda is a named, global
    entity, any lambda can invoke any other:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<SQUARE>[x:int]#{
    \return{\mul{${x}, ${x}}}
}

\lambda<SUM_OF_SQUARES>[a:int, b:int]#{
    \return{\add{
        \invoke<SQUARE>[${a}],
        \invoke<SQUARE>[${b}]
    }}
}

$3^2 + 4^2$ = \invoke<SUM_OF_SQUARES>[3, 4]
|}{%
    \lambda<SQUARE>[x:int]#{
        \return{\mul{${x}, ${x}}}
    }
    \lambda<SUM_OF_SQUARES>[a:int, b:int]#{
        \return{\add{
            \invoke<SQUARE>[${a}],
            \invoke<SQUARE>[${b}]
        }}
    }
    \indented{
        $3^2 + 4^2$ = \invoke<SUM_OF_SQUARES>[3, 4]
    }
}

    \cmd{invoke} calls nest freely. Here \textit{SUM\_OF\_SQUARES} calls
    \textit{SQUARE} twice, and the results flow back through the \cmd{add}.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{The Type System}}

    CL has six types. Every variable must be typed on its first declaration;
    subsequent reassignments may omit the type:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{int} -- 64-bit signed integer, the workhorse type
        - \textbf{string} -- immutable UTF-8 text
        - \textbf{int[]} -- mutable integer array
        - \textbf{string[]} -- mutable string array
        - \textbf{map} -- Robin Hood hash map (integer keys and values)
        - \textbf{address} -- a handle to a collection, for passing by reference
    }}

    \hylst{\verb~
\lambda<TYPES>[]#{
    \let<x:int>{42}
    \let<s:string>{hello}
    \let<arr:int[]>{[10, 20, 30]}
    \let<m:map>{|1->100, 2->200|}

    \let<x>{99}   % reassign: type already known
    \return{${x}}
}

\invoke<TYPES>[]
~}{%
    \lambda<TYPES>[]#{
        \let<x:int>{42}
        \let<s:string>{hello}
        \let<arr:int[]>{[10, 20, 30]}
        \let<m:map>{|1->100, 2->200|}
        \let<x>{99}
        \return{${x}}
    }
    \indented{
        \invoke<TYPES>[]
    }
}

    Variable access is always \$\{name\} -- the same syntax as the macro
    system, so muscle memory transfers directly.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{OLD SYNTAX IS BANNED}
    Inside \#\{\} blocks, the old \cmd{valueof}\<x\> and \cmd{recall}\<x\>
    commands are rejected by the parser with helpful error messages. This
    keeps CL code clean and unambiguous. The old syntax still works in
    regular macro bodies.
    \end{didyouknow}

    \fculn{Type Annotations on Parameters}

    Parameters carry the same type annotations. The type goes after a colon:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\lambda<fn>[name:type, name:type]#{ ... }
|}

    The type tells Subnivean how to allocate storage and which operations
    are valid. Passing the wrong type causes a runtime coercion -- integers
    convert to their string representation, strings parse to integers when
    possible (defaulting to 0).

    \fculn{Reassignment}

    After the first \cmd{let} with a type, later assignments omit it:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\let<x:int>{1}        % first time: typed
\let<x>{2}            % reassign: type known
\let<x>{\add{${x},3}} % computed reassignment
|}

    Attempting to re-declare the type is harmless but unnecessary.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Arithmetic, Comparison, and Logic}}

    CL provides the same operators available in the macro system. Inside
    \#\{\} blocks they compile to direct bytecode operations instead of
    text expansion, making them substantially faster.

    \fculn{Arithmetic}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{add}\{a,b\}:\quad addition
        - \cmd{sub}\{a,b\}:\quad subtraction
        - \cmd{mul}\{a,b\}:\quad multiplication
        - \cmd{div}\{a,b\}:\quad integer division (rounds toward zero)
        - \cmd{mod}\{a,b\}:\quad remainder after division
        - \cmd{neg}\{a\}:\quad negation ($-a$)
        - \cmd{max}\{a,b\}:\quad the larger value
        - \cmd{min}\{a,b\}:\quad the smaller value
        - \cmd{rand}\{n\}:\quad random integer in [0, $n$)
    }}

    \fculn{Comparisons}

    All comparisons return 1 for true, 0 for false:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{eq}\{a,b\}, \cmd{ne}\{a,b\}:\quad equal, not equal
        - \cmd{lt}\{a,b\}, \cmd{le}\{a,b\}:\quad less than, less-or-equal
        - \cmd{gt}\{a,b\}, \cmd{ge}\{a,b\}:\quad greater than, greater-or-equal
    }}

    \fculn{Logic}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{and}\{a,b\}:\quad logical AND (1 iff both nonzero)
        - \cmd{or}\{a,b\}:\quad logical OR (1 iff either nonzero)
        - \cmd{not}\{a\}:\quad logical NOT (1 if zero, 0 if nonzero)
    }}

    These nest naturally. A condition like "x is between 1 and 100" reads:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<IN_RANGE>[x:int]#{
    \return{\and{\ge{${x}, 1}, \le{${x}, 100}}}
}

in range: \invoke<IN_RANGE>[42] \\
out of range: \invoke<IN_RANGE>[200]
|}{%
    \lambda<IN_RANGE>[x:int]#{
        \return{\and{\ge{${x}, 1}, \le{${x}, 100}}}
    }
    \indented{
        in range: \invoke<IN_RANGE>[42] \\
        out of range: \invoke<IN_RANGE>[200]
    }
}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Control Flow}}

    \fculn{Conditionals}

    The \cmd{if}/\cmd{else} structure works identically to the macro system:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\if{condition}{true branch}\else{false branch}
|}

    Zero is false, every other integer is true. The \cmd{else} branch is
    optional. The placement rule applies here too: \cmd{else} must
    immediately follow the closing brace of the true branch with no
    intervening whitespace.

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<ABS>[x:int]#{
    \if{\lt{${x}, 0}}{
        \return{\sub{0, ${x}}}
    }\else{
        \return{${x}}
    }
}

abs(-42) = \invoke<ABS>[-42] \\
abs(7) = \invoke<ABS>[7]
|}{%
    \lambda<ABS>[x:int]#{
        \if{\lt{${x}, 0}}{
            \return{\sub{0, ${x}}}
        }\else{
            \return{${x}}
        }
    }
    \indented{
        abs(-42) = \invoke<ABS>[-42] \\
        abs(7) = \invoke<ABS>[7]
    }
}

    Conditionals nest for multi-way branching. A nested chain acts like a
    switch statement:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<CLASSIFY>[n:int]#{
    \if{\lt{${n}, 0}}{
        \return{-1}
    }\else{\if{\eq{${n}, 0}}{
        \return{0}
    }\else{
        \return{1}
    }}
}

sign(-5) = \invoke<CLASSIFY>[-5] \\
sign(0) = \invoke<CLASSIFY>[0] \\
sign(99) = \invoke<CLASSIFY>[99]
|}{%
    \lambda<CLASSIFY>[n:int]#{
        \if{\lt{${n}, 0}}{
            \return{-1}
        }\else{\if{\eq{${n}, 0}}{
            \return{0}
        }\else{
            \return{1}
        }}
    }
    \indented{
        sign(-5) = \invoke<CLASSIFY>[-5] \\
        sign(0) = \invoke<CLASSIFY>[0] \\
        sign(99) = \invoke<CLASSIFY>[99]
    }
}

    \fculn{Loops}

    The loop construct runs a body repeatedly until an exit condition fires:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\begin{loop}
    \exit_when{condition}
    body
\end{loop}
|}

    \cmd{exit\_when} checks its condition at the top of every iteration.
    When the condition becomes true, control jumps past \cmd{end}\{loop\}
    immediately -- the body does not execute for that iteration.

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<FACTORIAL>[n:int]#{
    \let<result:int>{1}
    \let<i:int>{${n}}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\le{${i}, 1}}
        \let<result>{\mul{${result}, ${i}}}
        \dec<i>
    \end{loop}
    \return{${result}}
}

5! = \invoke<FACTORIAL>[5] \\
10! = \invoke<FACTORIAL>[10]
|}{%
    \lambda<FACTORIAL>[n:int]#{
        \let<result:int>{1}
        \let<i:int>{${n}}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\le{${i}, 1}}
            \let<result>{\mul{${result}, ${i}}}
            \dec<i>
        \end{loop}
        \return{${result}}
    }
    \indented{
        5! = \invoke<FACTORIAL>[5] \\
        10! = \invoke<FACTORIAL>[10]
    }
}

    Loops are the primary iteration mechanism. There is no for loop or
    while loop -- \cmd{begin}\{loop\} with \cmd{exit\_when} covers all
    cases. The pattern is always: initialize a counter before the loop,
    test it with \cmd{exit\_when}, and advance it in the body.

    Here is the iterative Fibonacci sequence, an accumulator pattern:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<FIB>[n:int]#{
    \if{\le{${n}, 1}}{
        \return{${n}}
    }
    \let<a:int>{0}
    \let<b:int>{1}
    \let<i:int>{2}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\gt{${i}, ${n}}}
        \let<temp:int>{${b}}
        \let<b>{\add{${a}, ${b}}}
        \let<a>{${temp}}
        \inc<i>
    \end{loop}
    \return{${b}}
}

fib(0) = \invoke<FIB>[0] \\
fib(1) = \invoke<FIB>[1] \\
fib(10) = \invoke<FIB>[10]
|}{%
    \lambda<FIB>[n:int]#{
        \if{\le{${n}, 1}}{
            \return{${n}}
        }
        \let<a:int>{0}
        \let<b:int>{1}
        \let<i:int>{2}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\gt{${i}, ${n}}}
            \let<temp:int>{${b}}
            \let<b>{\add{${a}, ${b}}}
            \let<a>{${temp}}
            \inc<i>
        \end{loop}
        \return{${b}}
    }
    \indented{
        fib(0) = \invoke<FIB>[0] \\
        fib(1) = \invoke<FIB>[1] \\
        fib(10) = \invoke<FIB>[10]
    }
}

    The guard clause at the top handles the base cases with an early
    \cmd{return}. The accumulator loop then slides two variables forward
    through the sequence without recursion.

    One more classic: the Euclidean GCD.

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<GCD>[a:int, b:int]#{
    \let<x:int>{${a}}
    \let<y:int>{${b}}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\eq{${y}, 0}}
        \let<temp:int>{\mod{${x}, ${y}}}
        \let<x>{${y}}
        \let<y>{${temp}}
    \end{loop}
    \return{${x}}
}

gcd(48, 18) = \invoke<GCD>[48, 18] \\
gcd(100, 25) = \invoke<GCD>[100, 25]
|}{%
    \lambda<GCD>[a:int, b:int]#{
        \let<x:int>{${a}}
        \let<y:int>{${b}}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\eq{${y}, 0}}
            \let<temp:int>{\mod{${x}, ${y}}}
            \let<x>{${y}}
            \let<y>{${temp}}
        \end{loop}
        \return{${x}}
    }
    \indented{
        gcd(48, 18) = \invoke<GCD>[48, 18] \\
        gcd(100, 25) = \invoke<GCD>[100, 25]
    }
}

    The algorithm repeatedly replaces the pair ($x$, $y$) with ($y$,
    $x \bmod y$) until $y$ reaches zero. At that point $x$ holds the
    greatest common divisor.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{EARLY RETURN}
    \cmd{return} is not limited to the end of a function. It exits the
    current lambda immediately from wherever it appears -- inside a loop,
    inside a conditional, anywhere. This is useful for guard clauses:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\lambda<SAFE_DIV>[a:int, b:int]#{
    \if{\eq{${b}, 0}}{\return{0}}
    \return{\div{${a}, ${b}}}
}
|}
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Arrays}}

    Arrays are ordered, mutable sequences with O(1) random access. Declare
    one by appending [] to the type name:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<ARRAY_SUM>[]#{
    \let<nums:int[]>{[10, 20, 30, 40, 50]}
    \let<sum:int>{0}
    \let<i:int>{0}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\ge{${i}, \len<nums>}}
        \let<sum>{\add{${sum}, \at<nums>[${i}]}}
        \inc<i>
    \end{loop}
    \return{${sum}}
}

Sum: \invoke<ARRAY_SUM>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<ARRAY_SUM>[]#{
        \let<nums:int[]>{[10, 20, 30, 40, 50]}
        \let<sum:int>{0}
        \let<i:int>{0}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\ge{${i}, \len<nums>}}
            \let<sum>{\add{${sum}, \at<nums>[${i}]}}
            \inc<i>
        \end{loop}
        \return{${sum}}
    }
    \indented{
        Sum: \invoke<ARRAY_SUM>[]
    }
}

    The key operations:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{at}\<arr\>[index] -- read an element
        - \cmd{set}\<arr\>[index]\{value\} -- write an element
        - \cmd{len}\<arr\> -- the number of elements
    }}

    Array indices are zero-based. Reading past the end returns 0; writing
    past the end is silently ignored.

    \fculn{Finding a Maximum}

    A common pattern: iterate an array tracking the best value seen so far.

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<FIND_MAX>[]#{
    \let<arr:int[]>{[34, 12, 78, 5, 91, 23]}
    \let<best:int>{\at<arr>[0]}
    \let<i:int>{1}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\ge{${i}, \len<arr>}}
        \if{\gt{\at<arr>[${i}], ${best}}}{
            \let<best>{\at<arr>[${i}]}
        }
        \inc<i>
    \end{loop}
    \return{${best}}
}

Maximum: \invoke<FIND_MAX>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<FIND_MAX>[]#{
        \let<arr:int[]>{[34, 12, 78, 5, 91, 23]}
        \let<best:int>{\at<arr>[0]}
        \let<i:int>{1}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\ge{${i}, \len<arr>}}
            \if{\gt{\at<arr>[${i}], ${best}}}{
                \let<best>{\at<arr>[${i}]}
            }
            \inc<i>
        \end{loop}
        \return{${best}}
    }
    \indented{
        Maximum: \invoke<FIND_MAX>[]
    }
}

    \fculn{Modifying Elements}

    \cmd{set} writes a value at a given index:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<ARR_MODIFY>[]#{
    \let<arr:int[]>{[1, 2, 3]}
    \set<arr>[1]{99}
    \return{\at<arr>[1]}
}

After set: \invoke<ARR_MODIFY>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<ARR_MODIFY>[]#{
        \let<arr:int[]>{[1, 2, 3]}
        \set<arr>[1]{99}
        \return{\at<arr>[1]}
    }
    \indented{
        After set: \invoke<ARR_MODIFY>[]
    }
}

    \fculn{String Arrays}

    Arrays can also hold strings:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<STR_ARR>[]#{
    \let<words:string[]>{[hello, world, CL]}
    \return{\at<words>[2]}
}

Third word: \invoke<STR_ARR>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<STR_ARR>[]#{
        \let<words:string[]>{[hello, world, CL]}
        \return{\at<words>[2]}
    }
    \indented{
        Third word: \invoke<STR_ARR>[]
    }
}

    String arrays use \textit{string[]} as the type. Access and mutation
    work identically to integer arrays.

    \fculn{Stack Operations}

    Arrays double as stacks with LIFO (last-in, first-out) semantics:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{push}\<arr\>\{value\} -- append to end
        - \cmd{pop}\<arr\> -- remove and return the last element
        - \cmd{peek}\<arr\> -- read the last element without removing
        - \cmd{len}\<arr\> -- the current depth
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
\push<COLORS>{red}
\push<COLORS>{green}
\push<COLORS>{blue}

Peek: \peek<COLORS> \\
Pop: \pop<COLORS>, \pop<COLORS>, \pop<COLORS> \\
Length after: \len<COLORS>
|}{%
    \push<COLORS>{red}
    \push<COLORS>{green}
    \push<COLORS>{blue}
    \indented{
        Peek: \peek<COLORS> \\
        Pop: \pop<COLORS>, \pop<COLORS>, \pop<COLORS> \\
        Length after: \len<COLORS>
    }
}

    Popping and peeking an empty stack returns an empty string. This
    makes stacks safe to drain in a loop without bounds checking.

    \fculn{Queue Operations}

    For FIFO (first-in, first-out) ordering, use the queue interface:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{enqueue}\<arr\>\{value\} -- append to back
        - \cmd{dequeue}\<arr\> -- remove and return from the front
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
\enqueue<TASKS>{compile}
\enqueue<TASKS>{link}
\enqueue<TASKS>{test}

Order: \dequeue<TASKS>, \dequeue<TASKS>, \dequeue<TASKS>
|}{%
    \enqueue<TASKS>{compile}
    \enqueue<TASKS>{link}
    \enqueue<TASKS>{test}
    \indented{
        Order: \dequeue<TASKS>, \dequeue<TASKS>, \dequeue<TASKS>
    }
}

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{STACK vs. QUEUE}
    Both operate on the same underlying array. The only difference is
    which end the removal draws from: \cmd{pop} takes from the back
    (LIFO), \cmd{dequeue} takes from the front (FIFO). You can freely
    mix \cmd{push} with either \cmd{pop} or \cmd{dequeue} on the same
    array if your algorithm calls for it.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Maps}}

    Maps are Robin Hood hash tables mapping integer keys to integer values.
    They provide O(1) average-case lookup, insertion, and deletion. Maps
    are declared with pipe-delimited literal syntax:

    \hylst{\verb~
\lambda<MAP_DEMO>[]#{
    \let<m:map>{|1->100, 2->200, 3->300|}
    \return{\at<m>[2]}
}

Value at key 2: \invoke<MAP_DEMO>[]
~}{%
    \lambda<MAP_DEMO>[]#{
        \let<m:map>{|1->100, 2->200, 3->300|}
        \return{\at<m>[2]}
    }
    \indented{
        Value at key 2: \invoke<MAP_DEMO>[]
    }
}

    The operations mirror array access with additional map-specific
    commands:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{at}\<m\>[key] -- read the value for a key
        - \cmd{set}\<m\>[key]\{value\} -- write a value for a key
        - \cmd{len}\<m\> -- the number of entries
        - \cmd{map\_has}\<m\>[key] -- 1 if the key exists, 0 otherwise
        - \cmd{map\_del}\<m\>[key] -- delete a key-value pair
        - \cmd{map\_keys}\<m\> -- all keys as a heap array
    }}

    An empty map is written as \verb~||~.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{VERBATIM AND MAPS}
    Map literals use pipe characters, which conflict with the default
    \cmd{verb} delimiter. When showing map code in a verbatim block,
    use a different delimiter: \cmd{verb}\textasciitilde{}...\textasciitilde{} works well.
    \end{didyouknow}

    \fculn{Membership and Deletion}

    \cmd{map\_has} tests whether a key exists without reading its value.
    \cmd{map\_del} removes a key entirely:

    \hylst{\verb~
\lambda<MAP_OPS>[]#{
    \let<m:map>{|10->1, 20->2, 30->3|}
    \let<before:int>{\map_has<m>[20]}
    \map_del<m>[20]
    \let<after:int>{\map_has<m>[20]}
    \return{\add{\mul{${before}, 10}, ${after}}}
}

before=1, after=0 encoded as: \invoke<MAP_OPS>[]
~}{%
    \lambda<MAP_OPS>[]#{
        \let<m:map>{|10->1, 20->2, 30->3|}
        \let<before:int>{\map_has<m>[20]}
        \map_del<m>[20]
        \let<after:int>{\map_has<m>[20]}
        \return{\add{\mul{${before}, 10}, ${after}}}
    }
    \indented{
        before=1, after=0 encoded as: \invoke<MAP_OPS>[]
    }
}

    The return value 10 encodes both results: \cmd{map\_has} returned 1
    before deletion and 0 after.

    \fculn{Iterating over a Map}

    Maps have no built-in iterator. Instead, extract the keys with
    \cmd{map\_keys}, which returns a heap-allocated array of all keys:

    \hylst{\verb~
\lambda<MAP_SUM>[]#{
    \let<m:map>{|1->10, 2->20, 3->30|}
    \let<keys:int>{\map_keys<m>}
    \let<n:int>{\mem_len{${keys}}}
    \let<sum:int>{0}
    \let<i:int>{0}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\ge{${i}, ${n}}}
        \let<key:int>{\mem_load{${keys}, ${i}}}
        \let<sum>{\add{${sum}, \at<m>[${key}]}}
        \inc<i>
    \end{loop}
    \return{${sum}}
}

Map value sum: \invoke<MAP_SUM>[]
~}{%
    \lambda<MAP_SUM>[]#{
        \let<m:map>{|1->10, 2->20, 3->30|}
        \let<keys:int>{\map_keys<m>}
        \let<n:int>{\mem_len{${keys}}}
        \let<sum:int>{0}
        \let<i:int>{0}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\ge{${i}, ${n}}}
            \let<key:int>{\mem_load{${keys}, ${i}}}
            \let<sum>{\add{${sum}, \at<m>[${key}]}}
            \inc<i>
        \end{loop}
        \return{${sum}}
    }
    \indented{
        Map value sum: \invoke<MAP_SUM>[]
    }
}

    Notice that \cmd{map\_keys} returns a \textit{heap address}, not a
    regular array. This is why we use \cmd{mem\_load} to access individual
    keys and \cmd{mem\_len} for the count. Heap memory is explained in
    detail in its own section below.

    \fculn{A Frequency Counter}

    Maps excel at counting. Here is a frequency counter that tallies how
    many times each value appears in an array:

    \hylst{\verb~
\lambda<FREQ>[]#{
    \let<data:int[]>{[3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6, 5, 3, 5]}
    \let<freq:map>{||}
    \let<i:int>{0}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\ge{${i}, \len<data>}}
        \let<val:int>{\at<data>[${i}]}
        \if{\map_has<freq>[${val}]}{
            \set<freq>[${val}]{\add{\at<freq>[${val}], 1}}
        }\else{
            \set<freq>[${val}]{1}
        }
        \inc<i>
    \end{loop}
    \return{\at<freq>[5]}
}

Count of 5: \invoke<FREQ>[]
~}{%
    \lambda<FREQ>[]#{
        \let<data:int[]>{[3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6, 5, 3, 5]}
        \let<freq:map>{||}
        \let<i:int>{0}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\ge{${i}, \len<data>}}
            \let<val:int>{\at<data>[${i}]}
            \if{\map_has<freq>[${val}]}{
                \set<freq>[${val}]{\add{\at<freq>[${val}], 1}}
            }\else{
                \set<freq>[${val}]{1}
            }
            \inc<i>
        \end{loop}
        \return{\at<freq>[5]}
    }
    \indented{
        Count of 5: \invoke<FREQ>[]
    }
}

    The value 5 appears three times in the input, so the count is 3. The
    pattern -- check with \cmd{map\_has}, then either increment or
    initialize -- is the standard approach for map-based accumulators.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Address Passing}}

    By default, collections passed to a lambda are copied. When you need a
    function to modify the caller's array or map, pass an \textit{address}
    instead:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<FILL>[addr:address, n:int, val:int]#{
    \let<i:int>{0}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\ge{${i}, ${n}}}
        \set<*addr>[${i}]{${val}}
        \inc<i>
    \end{loop}
}

\lambda<DEMO_ADDR>[]#{
    \let<arr:int[]>{[0, 0, 0, 0, 0]}
    \invoke<FILL>[\addressof<arr>, 5, 42]
    \return{\at<arr>[2]}
}

After fill: \invoke<DEMO_ADDR>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<FILL>[addr:address, n:int, val:int]#{
        \let<i:int>{0}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\ge{${i}, ${n}}}
            \set<*addr>[${i}]{${val}}
            \inc<i>
        \end{loop}
    }
    \lambda<DEMO_ADDR>[]#{
        \let<arr:int[]>{[0, 0, 0, 0, 0]}
        \invoke<FILL>[\addressof<arr>, 5, 42]
        \return{\at<arr>[2]}
    }
    \indented{
        After fill: \invoke<DEMO_ADDR>[]
    }
}

    The key pieces:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{addressof}\<name\> -- obtains the address of a collection
        - \cmd{at}\<*addr\>[i] -- dereferences the address to read
        - \cmd{set}\<*addr\>[i]\{v\} -- dereferences the address to write
    }}

    The asterisk in \<*addr\> is the dereference operator, analogous to
    C's pointer dereference. When \textit{FILL} writes through \<*addr\>,
    it modifies the original \textit{arr} in the caller's scope.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{TWO KINDS OF INDIRECTION}
    CL supports two dereference patterns. \cmd{addressof} gives a handle
    to a collection -- suitable for arrays and maps. String-based
    indirection lets a string variable hold the \textit{name} of another
    variable: \cmd{inc}\<*name\> increments whatever variable the string
    names. Both use the * prefix, but they operate at different levels.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Dynamic Variable Names}}

    Sometimes you need to address variables whose names are constructed at
    runtime. CL supports nested \$\{\} expressions for computed names:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<DYN_ACCESS>[]#{
    \let<item0:int>{100}
    \let<item1:int>{200}
    \let<item2:int>{300}
    \let<i:int>{1}
    \return{${item${i}}}
}

Item 1: \invoke<DYN_ACCESS>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<DYN_ACCESS>[]#{
        \let<item0:int>{100}
        \let<item1:int>{200}
        \let<item2:int>{300}
        \let<i:int>{1}
        \return{${item${i}}}
    }
    \indented{
        Item 1: \invoke<DYN_ACCESS>[]
    }
}

    The expression \verb|${item${i}}| first evaluates the inner
    \verb|${i}| to get 1, then concatenates to form \textit{item1}, and
    finally looks up that variable. This is essentially computed variable
    names.

    The pattern extends to multiple indices. A 2D grid stored in flat
    variables:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<GRID_2D>[]#{
    \let<cell00:int>{11}
    \let<cell01:int>{12}
    \let<cell10:int>{21}
    \let<cell11:int>{22}
    \let<sum:int>{0}
    \let<r:int>{0}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\ge{${r}, 2}}
        \let<c:int>{0}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\ge{${c}, 2}}
            \let<sum>{\add{${sum}, ${cell${r}${c}}}}
            \inc<c>
        \end{loop}
        \inc<r>
    \end{loop}
    \return{${sum}}
}

Grid sum: \invoke<GRID_2D>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<GRID_2D>[]#{
        \let<cell00:int>{11}
        \let<cell01:int>{12}
        \let<cell10:int>{21}
        \let<cell11:int>{22}
        \let<sum:int>{0}
        \let<r:int>{0}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\ge{${r}, 2}}
            \let<c:int>{0}
            \begin{loop}
                \exit_when{\ge{${c}, 2}}
                \let<sum>{\add{${sum}, ${cell${r}${c}}}}
                \inc<c>
            \end{loop}
            \inc<r>
        \end{loop}
        \return{${sum}}
    }
    \indented{
        Grid sum: \invoke<GRID_2D>[]
    }
}

    \verb|${cell${r}${c}}| resolves both indices: when $r=1$ and $c=0$
    it becomes \textit{cell10}, yielding 21.

    \fculn{Dynamic Mutation}

    Dynamic names also work with mutators.
    \verb|\inc<${slot${target}}>| increments whichever variable the
    index resolves to:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<DYN_INC>[]#{
    \let<slot0:int>{0}
    \let<slot1:int>{0}
    \let<slot2:int>{0}
    \let<i:int>{0}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\ge{${i}, 30}}
        \let<target:int>{\mod{${i}, 3}}
        \inc<${slot${target}}>
        \inc<i>
    \end{loop}
    \return{\add{\add{${slot0}, ${slot1}}, ${slot2}}}
}

30 across 3 slots: \invoke<DYN_INC>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<DYN_INC>[]#{
        \let<slot0:int>{0}
        \let<slot1:int>{0}
        \let<slot2:int>{0}
        \let<i:int>{0}
        \begin{loop}
            \exit_when{\ge{${i}, 30}}
            \let<target:int>{\mod{${i}, 3}}
            \inc<${slot${target}}>
            \inc<i>
        \end{loop}
        \return{\add{\add{${slot0}, ${slot1}}, ${slot2}}}
    }
    \indented{
        30 across 3 slots: \invoke<DYN_INC>[]
    }
}

    Each iteration increments a different slot based on
    $i \bmod 3$. After 30 iterations, each slot holds 10, and the total
    is 30.

    \fculn{String-Based Indirection}

    A separate pattern uses a string variable that holds the name of
    another variable. The * prefix dereferences the name:

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<STR_DEREF>[]#{
    \let<counter:int>{0}
    \let<name:string>{counter}
    \inc<*name>
    \inc<*name>
    \inc<*name>
    \return{${counter}}
}

Result: \invoke<STR_DEREF>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<STR_DEREF>[]#{
        \let<counter:int>{0}
        \let<name:string>{counter}
        \inc<*name>
        \inc<*name>
        \inc<*name>
        \return{${counter}}
    }
    \indented{
        Result: \invoke<STR_DEREF>[]
    }
}

    \cmd{inc}\<*name\> looks up the string stored in \textit{name} --
    which is \verb|"counter"| -- and increments that variable. Three
    increments bring \textit{counter} from 0 to 3.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Heap Memory}}

    CL provides manual heap allocation for data that needs to persist
    across lambda calls or that is too large for the scope system. The
    heap is a flat address space of integer slots:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{mem\_alloc}\{size\} -- allocate a block, returns an address
        - \cmd{mem\_store}\{addr, index, value\} -- write to a slot
        - \cmd{mem\_load}\{addr, index\} -- read from a slot
        - \cmd{mem\_len}\{addr\} -- the number of slots in the block
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
\lambda<HEAP_DEMO>[]#{
    \let<buf:int>{\mem_alloc{5}}
    \mem_store{${buf}, 0, 42}
    \mem_store{${buf}, 1, 99}
    \return{\add{
        \mem_load{${buf}, 0},
        \mem_load{${buf}, 1}
    }}
}

Heap sum: \invoke<HEAP_DEMO>[]
|}{%
    \lambda<HEAP_DEMO>[]#{
        \let<buf:int>{\mem_alloc{5}}
        \mem_store{${buf}, 0, 42}
        \mem_store{${buf}, 1, 99}
        \return{\add{
            \mem_load{${buf}, 0},
            \mem_load{${buf}, 1}
        }}
    }
    \indented{
        Heap sum: \invoke<HEAP_DEMO>[]
    }
}

    Heap blocks persist for the document's lifetime. Once allocated, the
    address can be stored in a variable and passed between lambdas. The
    Matrix Digital Rain example later in this guide uses the heap as a
    virtual screen buffer -- each cell is a packed integer holding both a
    character index and a color tier.

    You already encountered heap memory indirectly: \cmd{map\_keys}
    returns a heap address. That is why the map iteration pattern uses
    \cmd{mem\_load} and \cmd{mem\_len} to traverse the key array.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{HEAP vs. ARRAYS}
    Arrays (\cmd{let}\<arr:int[]\>\{...\}) live in the VM's scope
    system and are garbage-collected when their scope ends. Heap blocks
    (\cmd{mem\_alloc}) persist globally. Use arrays for local data
    within a single lambda; use the heap when data must survive across
    calls or when you need to share large buffers between lambdas.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Output Operations}}

    Most lambdas compute and return values. But CL also supports direct
    terminal output for building interactive applications:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{emit}\{expr\} -- output a value as text
        - \cmd{cursor}\{row, col\} -- move the terminal cursor (1-based)
        - \cmd{ansi}\{codes\} -- emit an ANSI escape sequence
    }}

    These commands bypass the normal typesetting pipeline and write
    directly to the terminal. They are the foundation of real-time
    programs like Matrix Digital Rain and Game of Life.

    \fculn{ANSI Color Codes}

    \cmd{ansi} accepts standard ANSI SGR codes:

    \indented{
        \table[width:50,pad:{l:1,r:1},frame:single]{
            \row[frame:{b:double}]{
                \col{Code}
                \col{Effect}
            }
            \row{
                \col{0}
                \col{Reset all attributes}
            }
            \row{
                \col{1}
                \col{Bold}
            }
            \row{
                \col{3}
                \col{Italic}
            }
            \row{
                \col{4}
                \col{Underline}
            }
            \row{
                \col{31--37}
                \col{Foreground colors (red..white)}
            }
            \row{
                \col{90--97}
                \col{Bright foreground colors}
            }
            \row{
                \col{40--47}
                \col{Background colors}
            }
        }
    }

    Multiple codes can be combined with semicolons:
    \cmd{ansi}\{92;40\} sets bright green foreground on black background.

    The stdlib also provides friendlier wrappers:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\term_fg[red]{text}
\term_bg[blue]{text}
\term_color[fg=white,bg=red]{text}
\term_bold{text}
\term_underline{text}
\term_inverse{text}
|}

    \fculn{Cursor Control}

    Beyond \cmd{cursor}\{row, col\}, a full suite of positioning commands
    is available:

    \indented{
        \table[width:50,pad:{l:1,r:1},frame:single]{
            \row[frame:{b:double}]{
                \col{Command}
                \col{Effect}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{cursor\_up}\{n\}}
                \col{Move up n lines}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{cursor\_down}\{n\}}
                \col{Move down n lines}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{cursor\_left}\{n\}}
                \col{Move left n columns}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{cursor\_right}\{n\}}
                \col{Move right n columns}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{cursor\_save}}
                \col{Save cursor position}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{cursor\_restore}}
                \col{Restore saved position}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{cursor\_hide} / \cmd{cursor\_show}}
                \col{Toggle cursor visibility}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{clear\_screen}}
                \col{Clear entire screen}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{clear\_line} / \cmd{clear\_to\_eol}}
                \col{Clear current line / to end}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{term\_rows} / \cmd{term\_cols}}
                \col{Terminal dimensions}
            }
        }
    }


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{The Main Loop}}

    Interactive programs use \cmd{main}\{body\}. This puts the terminal
    into alternate screen mode and runs the body in an infinite loop,
    clearing the screen between frames:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\main{
    % Process input
    \if{\haskey}{
        \let<k>{\getkey}
        \if{\streq{${k},q}}{\exit}
    }
    % Compute
    \invoke<UPDATE>[...]
    % Render
    \invoke<DRAW>[...]
    \wait{30}   % ~33 fps
}
|}

    The architecture is always: read input, compute the next state, render
    the frame, sleep. Input commands include:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{haskey} -- 1 if a keypress is waiting
        - \cmd{getkey} -- consume and return the next key
        - \cmd{getmouseX}, \cmd{getmouseY} -- mouse position
        - \cmd{getmousebutton} -- mouse button state (1=left, 3=right)
        - \cmd{exit} -- quit the program
        - \cmd{wait}\{ms\} -- pause for milliseconds
    }}

    The \cmd{main} loop manages the terminal lifecycle automatically:
    it enters alternate screen mode, enables raw input, and restores the
    terminal on exit. You just write the frame logic.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{CURSOR POSITIONING WITHOUT MAIN}
    You do not need \cmd{main} for simple cursor tricks. The cursor
    commands work in regular documents too -- useful for progress bars
    or status updates that overwrite themselves in place.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{The Interpreter/CL Bridge}}

    Programs do not have to be pure CL. The most powerful pattern in
    Hyades is mixing the text interpreter with compiled lambdas --
    letting each do what it does best. The interpreter handles
    initialization, configuration, and string processing. CL handles
    computation-heavy inner loops. The bridge between them is the
    \textit{persistent store}: heap blocks, maps, and arrays that both
    sides can access.

    \fculn{Allocating from the Interpreter}

    Heap memory and maps can only be \textit{created} inside a
    \verb|#{}| block (they are Subnivean operations). But you can wrap
    the allocation in a tiny lambda and call it from the interpreter:

    \fancylisting{\verb~
%%% Create a helper lambda that allocates and returns a heap address
\lambda<ALLOC>[size:int]#{\return{\mem_alloc{${size}}}}

%%% Interpreter allocates a buffer through the helper
\let<buf>{\invoke<ALLOC>[\mul{${COLS}, ${ROWS}}]}

%%% Maps are allocated with pipe literals inside #{}
\let<pos_map>#{||}
\let<spd_map>#{||}

%%% Arrays can be allocated directly with data
\let<grid>#{[0,0,1,0,0,1,1,1,0]}
~}

    After these lines, \verb|${buf}|, \verb|${pos_map}|,
    \verb|${spd_map}|, and \verb|${grid}| are ordinary integer
    addresses that the interpreter can store, pass, and hand to CL
    lambdas. The array form is especially convenient -- the non-sparse
    Game of Life uses \verb|\let<grid>#{[0,0,1,...]}| to create its
    initial board directly from the interpreter, yielding a heap array
    that CL lambdas can read and write via \cmd{mem\_load} and
    \cmd{mem\_store}.

    \fculn{Initialization in the Interpreter}

    The interpreter is often more convenient for setup code. Matrix
    Digital Rain initializes its column state with a simple loop in
    interpreter mode:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
%%% Initialize columns with random starting positions
\let<c>{0}
\begin{loop}
    \exit_when{\ge{${c}, ${COLS}}}
    \map_set<pos_map>{${c}, \sub{0, \rand{${ROWS}}}}
    \map_set<spd_map>{${c}, \add{1, \rand{3}}}
    \map_set<trail_map>{${c}, \add{8, \rand{24}}}
    \inc<c>
\end{loop}
|}

    This loop runs in the text interpreter -- no \verb|#{}|, no type
    annotations. It writes directly into the persistent maps using
    \cmd{map\_set}. Those same maps are later read by the compiled
    COMPUTE lambda through address dereferences (\verb|\at<*addr>[key]|).

    \fculn{Passing State Across the Boundary}

    The main loop ties everything together by passing persistent-store
    addresses as lambda parameters:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\main{
    \invoke<COMPUTE>[${COLS}, ${ROWS}, ${frame},
        ${buf}, ${pos_map}, ${spd_map},
        ${trail_map}, ${chr_map}]
    \invoke<RENDER>[${COLS}, ${ROWS}, ${buf}, ${K}]
    \inc<frame>
    \wait{60}
}
|}

    The interpreter owns the addresses; the CL lambdas receive them as
    plain integers. Inside the lambda, \verb|\at<*addr>[key]| reads
    through the address and \verb|\set<*addr>[key]{val}| writes back.
    Because both sides reference the same persistent store, changes made
    by COMPUTE are instantly visible to RENDER -- no copying required.

    \fculn{External Callbacks}

    How does this work under the hood? When a CL lambda dereferences an
    address, the Subnivean VM uses \textit{external callbacks} to reach
    into the interpreter:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{array\_lookup}: fetches an array by name from the
          interpreter's scope
        - \textbf{array\_set}: writes an element to an interpreter-owned
          array
        - \textbf{lambda\_compile}: compiles another lambda on demand
          when first referenced
    }}

    These callbacks fire transparently. When a CL lambda calls
    \verb|\invoke<OTHER_LAMBDA>[...]| and OTHER\_LAMBDA has not yet been
    compiled, the VM asks the interpreter to compile it, caches the
    result, and calls it at bytecode speed from then on.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{THE DESIGN PHILOSOPHY}
    The interpreter/CL split mirrors how CPU and GPU cooperate in
    graphics programming: the CPU (interpreter) sets up state and issues
    commands; the GPU (Subnivean VM) executes the heavy parallel work.
    You don't compile your configuration files to SPIR-V; you don't
    write your physics engine in shell script. Use each tool where it
    shines.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{The Subnivean Virtual Machine}}

    Every \#\{\} body is compiled to bytecode and executed by the Subnivean
    VM -- a stack-based virtual machine designed for mutable cells, lexical
    scopes, and closure semantics. Understanding Subnivean is not required
    for writing CL, but knowing what happens behind the scenes helps
    explain why CL is fast and why certain patterns perform better than
    others.

    \fculn{Why a VM?}

    The text interpreter processes macros by string expansion: each
    \cmd{valueof} call generates text, that text is spliced into the
    document, and the result is re-parsed. This is elegant for typesetting
    but catastrophically slow for computation. A simple loop running
    10{,}000 iterations generates and parses 10{,}000 strings.

    Subnivean bypasses text entirely. The compiler parses CL syntax into an
    AST, translates that AST into bytecode, and the VM executes the
    bytecode with a stack, scope chain, and register-like cells. There is
    no string generation, no re-parsing, no macro expansion overhead.

    The result is a \textbf{65× speedup}. Conway's Game of Life
    on a 5×5 grid for 1000 iterations:

    \indented{
        \table[width:40,pad:{l:1,r:1},frame:single]{
            \row[frame:{b:double}]{
                \col{Engine}
                \col[align:r]{Time}
            }
            \row{
                \col{Text interpreter}
                \col[align:r]{7.63s}
            }
            \row{
                \col{Subnivean VM}
                \col[align:r]{0.118s}
            }
        }
    }

    This is what makes interactive applications possible. Without
    Subnivean, Matrix Digital Rain could not maintain a usable frame rate.

    \fculn{The Compilation Pipeline}

    When Hyades encounters \#\{...\}, it:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - Parses the CL syntax into an abstract syntax tree (AST)
        - Compiles the AST to Subnivean bytecode instructions
        - Stores the bytecode in a function object
        - On each \cmd{invoke}, the VM executes the bytecode directly
    }}

    The compilation happens once at definition time. Subsequent calls run
    the pre-compiled bytecode with zero parsing overhead. This is
    analogous to how an ahead-of-time compiler works.

    \fculn{The Execution Model}

    The VM maintains five components:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - A \textbf{value stack} for operand computation
        - A \textbf{call stack} for function activation records
        - A \textbf{scope chain} for lexical variable resolution
        - A \textbf{symbol table} for interned identifiers
        - An \textbf{output buffer} for \cmd{emit} results
    }}

    Variables in CL are stored in \textit{cells} -- mutable boxes that
    live in the scope chain. When you write \cmd{let}\<x:int\>\{5\}, the
    compiler emits: push the value 5, create a new cell containing it,
    and bind the cell to the symbol "x" in the current scope. When you
    write \$\{x\}, it emits: look up the cell bound to "x", extract its
    value. Mutation (\cmd{inc}\<x\>) finds the cell and modifies it in
    place -- no allocation, no copying.

    \fculn{Closures and Scope Capture}

    Closures capture the scope at definition time. A lambda defined inside
    a loop captures the per-iteration scope, which means each closure gets
    its own copy of the loop variable. This is the same semantics as
    modern JavaScript's \textit{let} in a for loop -- each iteration
    creates a fresh scope, and each closure captures its own version.

    \fculn{External Callbacks}

    The VM communicates with the host Hyades interpreter through three
    callbacks: array lookup, array write, and lambda compilation. When CL
    code references a variable that does not exist in the VM's scope, the
    callback checks the interpreter's variable store. This is how lambdas
    access document-level variables -- counters, arrays, and maps defined
    outside any \#\{\} block are transparently available inside it.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{PERFORMANCE: INLINING}
    Function calls in Subnivean have overhead: scope creation, argument
    copying, stack frame setup. In tight inner loops -- thousands of
    iterations per frame -- this adds up. Both the Game of Life and
    Matrix Digital Rain inline their inner-loop logic rather than calling
    helper lambdas. When performance matters, prefer one large lambda
    over many small ones in hot paths.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Standard Library Functions}}

    The standard library includes pre-built CL functions in the STD::
    namespace. These cover common patterns so you do not have to write
    them yourself:

    \fculn{Array Generators}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - STD::RANGE[start, end] -- integers from start to end-1
        - STD::IOTA[n] -- integers from 0 to n-1
        - STD::REPEAT[n, val] -- n copies of a value
    }}

    \fculn{Aggregates}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - STD::SUM, STD::PRODUCT -- reduce an array
        - STD::MIN, STD::MAX, STD::AVG -- statistics
        - STD::LEN, STD::COUNT -- count elements
    }}

    \fculn{Transformations}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - STD::REVERSE, STD::MAP, STD::FILTER
        - STD::TAKE, STD::DROP, STD::SLICE
        - STD::SORT, STD::SORT\_DESC, STD::JOIN
    }}

    \fculn{Math Utilities}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - STD::ABS, STD::SIGN, STD::CLAMP
        - STD::POW, STD::FACTORIAL, STD::GCD, STD::LCM, STD::FIB
    }}

    \fculn{Formatting}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - STD::ORDINAL -- 1 \textrightarrow{} "1st", 2 \textrightarrow{} "2nd"
        - STD::ROMAN -- 42 \textrightarrow{} "XLII"
    }}

    \fculn{Predicates}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - STD::IS\_POSITIVE, STD::IS\_NEGATIVE, STD::IS\_ZERO
        - STD::IS\_EVEN, STD::IS\_ODD
    }}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{In Practice: Game of Life}}

    Conway's Game of Life is the canonical test of a computational system's
    expressiveness. The rules are simple: cells on a grid are either alive
    or dead, and their fate depends on how many neighbors they have. With
    just these rules, the system is Turing-complete -- capable of universal
    computation.

    The Hyades implementation uses a \textit{sparse} representation.
    Instead of allocating a huge 2D array, only live cells are stored in a
    map. The key is an encoded coordinate: row × 10000 + column.

    \fculn{Encoding Coordinates}

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\lambda<ENCODE_KEY>[row:int, col:int]#{
    \return{\add{\mul{${row}, 10000}, ${col}}}
}

\lambda<DECODE_ROW>[key:int]#{
    \return{\div{${key}, 10000}}
}

\lambda<DECODE_COL>[key:int]#{
    \return{\mod{${key}, 10000}}
}
|}

    A glider -- the simplest moving pattern -- is initialized as five map
    entries:

    \fancylisting{\verb~
\let<grid>#{|10002->1, 20003->1, 30001->1, 30002->1, 30003->1|}
\let<temp>#{||}
~}

    \fculn{The Step Function}

    The simulation step is the heart of the program. It works in three
    phases:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{Build candidates}: gather all live cells and their
          neighbors into a set. Only these cells can change state.
        - \textbf{Evaluate}: for each candidate, count its live neighbors
          and apply the rules (survive with 2--3 neighbors, birth with
          exactly 3).
        - \textbf{Swap}: clear the current grid and copy the results from
          a temporary map.
    }}

    The neighbor-counting loop iterates the 3×3 neighborhood
    with toroidal wrapping:

    \fancylisting{\verb~
%%% Count neighbors (inlined for performance)
\let<count:int>{0}
\let<dr:int>{-1}
\begin{loop}
    \exit_when{\gt{${dr}, 1}}
    \let<dc:int>{-1}
    \begin{loop}
        \exit_when{\gt{${dc}, 1}}
        \if{\and{\eq{${dr}, 0}, \eq{${dc}, 0}}}{}
        \else{
            \let<nr:int>{\mod{\add{\add{${row}, ${dr}},
                ${height}}, ${height}}}
            \let<nc:int>{\mod{\add{\add{${col}, ${dc}},
                ${width}}, ${width}}}
            \let<nkey:int>{\add{\mul{${nr}, 10000}, ${nc}}}
            \if{\map_has{${grid_map}, ${nkey}}}{\inc<count>}
        }
        \inc<dc>
    \end{loop}
    \inc<dr>
\end{loop}
~}

    The double \cmd{mod} with the added height/width ensures coordinates
    wrap around the grid edges -- a standard torus topology. The
    \cmd{map\_has} check is O(1) thanks to Robin Hood hashing.

    \fculn{The Next-State Rule}

    The Game of Life rule fits in a single conditional:

    \fancylisting{\verb~
\let<next:int>{
    \if{${current}}{
        \if{\or{\eq{${count}, 2},
                \eq{${count}, 3}}}{1}
        \else{0}
    }\else{
        \if{\eq{${count}, 3}}{1}
        \else{0}
    }
}
~}

    If a cell is alive, it survives with 2 or 3 neighbors. If dead, it is
    born with exactly 3. Everything else dies or stays dead.

    \fculn{Rendering}

    Each frame, the display lambda iterates every visible cell, queries the
    sparse map, and emits a colored block character:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\if{${is_hover}}{
    \if{${alive}}{\ansi{93}\emit{block}\ansi{0}}
    \else{\ansi{43;30}\emit{block}\ansi{0}}
}\else{
    \if{${alive}}{\ansi{92}\emit{block}\ansi{0}}
    \else{\ansi{90}\emit{block}\ansi{0}}
}
|}

    Alive cells are green; dead cells are dim gray; the cell under the
    mouse cursor is highlighted in yellow. The full implementation supports
    pausing, mouse interaction for toggling cells, and runs at 30+ fps on
    a standard terminal.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{TURING COMPLETENESS}
    The Game of Life is famously Turing-complete: any computation that a
    Turing machine can perform, a sufficiently large Life grid can also
    perform. The fact that Hyades can implement Life in CL -- with maps,
    loops, functions, and conditionals -- demonstrates that CL itself has
    the computational power to express arbitrary algorithms.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{In Practice: Matrix Digital Rain}}

    The Matrix Digital Rain is a more visually ambitious example. It
    renders falling columns of Katakana characters in green, mimicking the
    iconic effect from the film. This program exercises nearly every CL
    feature: arrays, maps, heap memory, address passing, ANSI colors, and
    cursor positioning.

    \fculn{Architecture}

    The program splits into two compiled lambdas:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{COMPUTE}: runs the physics simulation. For each column,
          it calculates which cells should be lit and at what brightness,
          writing packed values into a heap buffer.
        - \textbf{RENDER}: reads the heap buffer and emits ANSI-colored
          Katakana characters at the correct screen positions.
    }}

    This separation keeps computation pure and rendering straightforward.

    \fculn{The Virtual Screen Buffer}

    Rather than emitting characters during computation (which would mix
    logic with output), the program allocates a heap buffer sized to the
    terminal:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\lambda<ALLOC_BUF>[size:int]#{
    \return{\mem_alloc{${size}}}
}

\let<buf>{\invoke<ALLOC_BUF>[\mul{${COLS},${ROWS}}]}
|}

    Each cell in the buffer stores a packed integer:
    \textit{char\_index × 4 + color\_tier}. The COMPUTE lambda
    writes these packed values; the RENDER lambda unpacks them.

    \fculn{The Compute Lambda}

    COMPUTE takes eight parameters -- all by address so it can modify
    the shared state:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\lambda<COMPUTE>[cols:int, rows:int, frm:int,
    buf_addr:int, pos_addr:int, spd_addr:int,
    trail_addr:int, chr_addr:int]#{
    ...
}
|}

    For each column, it:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - Reads the current drop position and trail length from maps
        - Iterates the trail cells, calculating a color tier (bright white
          head \textrightarrow{} bright green \textrightarrow{} dark green
          \textrightarrow{} dim gray tail)
        - Picks a pseudo-random Katakana character for each cell
        - Packs the character index and color into a single integer
        - Writes the packed value into the heap buffer
        - Advances the drop position and resets when it scrolls off-screen
    }}

    The key technique is \textit{bit-packing}: a single integer encodes
    two values. The RENDER side unpacks with division and modulo:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\let<ch:int>{\div{${packed}, 4}}
\let<clr:int>{\mod{${packed}, 4}}
|}

    \fculn{The Render Lambda}

    RENDER reads the heap buffer and emits only non-zero cells. For each
    lit cell, it positions the cursor, selects the ANSI color, and emits
    the Katakana character by indexing into a string array:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\if{\eq{${clr}, 0}}{\ansi{97;40}}       % bright white head
\else{\if{\eq{${clr}, 1}}{\ansi{92;40}} % bright green
\else{\if{\eq{${clr}, 2}}{\ansi{32;40}} % dark green
\else{\ansi{90;40}}}}                    % dim gray
\emit{\at<*k_addr>[${ch}]}
|}

    The \<*k\_addr\> dereference reads from the Katakana array that was
    passed by address from the main loop.

    \fculn{The Main Loop}

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\main{
    \if{\haskey}{\let<k>{\getkey}
        \if{\streq{${k},q}}{\exit}
        \if{\streq{${k},Q}}{\exit}}
    \invoke<COMPUTE>[${COLS},${ROWS},${frame},
        ${buf},${pos_map},${spd_map},
        ${trail_map},${chr_map}]
    \invoke<RENDER>[${COLS},${ROWS},${buf},${K}]
    \inc<frame>
    \wait{60}
}
|}

    Each frame: check for quit, run the physics, draw the result, sleep
    60 milliseconds. Maps (positions, speeds, trail lengths, character
    seeds) are passed by address to COMPUTE, which updates them in place.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{BUFFER STRATEGY}
    The heap buffer acts as a "virtual framebuffer" -- COMPUTE writes
    packed cell data, RENDER reads it. This pattern avoids interleaving
    computation with terminal I/O, which would be both slower and harder
    to reason about. The buffer also enables selective rendering: only
    non-zero cells emit characters, so empty space costs nothing.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Naming Conventions}}

    CL follows a consistent naming scheme:

    \indented{
        \table[width:55,pad:{l:1,r:1},frame:single]{
            \row[frame:{b:double}]{
                \col{Category}
                \col{Convention}
                \col{Example}
            }
            \row{
                \col{Multi-word commands}
                \col{snake\_case}
                \col{\cmd{exit\_when}, \cmd{map\_has}}
            }
            \row{
                \col{Single-word commands}
                \col{lowercase}
                \col{\cmd{let}, \cmd{at}, \cmd{set}}
            }
            \row{
                \col{User lambda names}
                \col{UPPER\_CASE}
                \col{COMPUTE, GCD}
            }
            \row{
                \col{User local variables}
                \col{lower\_case}
                \col{count, row, i}
            }
        }
    }

    Uppercase names are global -- they persist between lambda calls and
    are visible everywhere. Lowercase names are local -- they exist only
    within their lambda's scope and are freed when the call returns.

    This is the same convention as the macro system, and for the same
    reason: Hyades uses casing to determine scope without requiring
    explicit scope annotations.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Quick Reference}}

    \indented{
        \table[width:70,pad:{l:1,r:1},frame:single]{
            \row[frame:{b:double}]{
                \col[width:35]{Command}
                \col{Description}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Definitions \& Calls}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{lambda}\<name\>[p:type]\#\{body\}}
                \col{Define a compiled function}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{invoke}\<name\>[args]}
                \col{Call a lambda}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{return}\{value\}}
                \col{Return from a lambda}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Variables}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{let}\<name:type\>\{value\}}
                \col{Declare a typed variable}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\$\{name\}}
                \col{Read a variable}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{inc}\<x\> / \cmd{dec}\<x\>}
                \col{Increment / decrement}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Arithmetic}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{add} \cmd{sub} \cmd{mul} \cmd{div} \cmd{mod}}
                \col{Basic arithmetic}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{neg}\{a\}}
                \col{Negation}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{max}\{a,b\} / \cmd{min}\{a,b\}}
                \col{Maximum / minimum}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{rand}\{n\}}
                \col{Random integer in [0, n)}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Comparisons \& Logic}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{eq} \cmd{ne} \cmd{lt} \cmd{le} \cmd{gt} \cmd{ge}}
                \col{Comparisons (return 0/1)}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{and}\{a,b\} / \cmd{or}\{a,b\} / \cmd{not}\{a\}}
                \col{Logic operators}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Control Flow}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{if}\{cond\}\{then\}\cmd{else}\{else\}}
                \col{Conditional}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{begin}\{loop\}...\cmd{end}\{loop\}}
                \col{Loop}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{exit\_when}\{condition\}}
                \col{Break from loop}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Collections}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{at}\<arr\>[i] / \cmd{set}\<arr\>[i]\{v\}}
                \col{Array/map read/write}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{len}\<arr\>}
                \col{Collection length}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{map\_has}\<m\>[k]}
                \col{Map membership test}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{map\_del}\<m\>[k]}
                \col{Delete map entry}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{map\_keys}\<m\>}
                \col{All keys (heap array)}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{push}\<arr\>\{v\} / \cmd{pop}\<arr\>}
                \col{Stack (LIFO) push/pop}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{peek}\<arr\>}
                \col{Read top without removing}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{enqueue}\<arr\>\{v\} / \cmd{dequeue}\<arr\>}
                \col{Queue (FIFO) add/remove}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Address Passing}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{addressof}\<name\>}
                \col{Get collection address}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{at}\<*a\>[i] / \cmd{set}\<*a\>[i]\{v\}}
                \col{Dereference read/write}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Heap Memory}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{mem\_alloc}\{n\}}
                \col{Allocate heap block}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{mem\_load}\{addr, i\}}
                \col{Read from heap}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{mem\_store}\{addr, i, v\}}
                \col{Write to heap}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{mem\_len}\{addr\}}
                \col{Heap block length}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Terminal Output}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{emit}\{text\}}
                \col{Output a value}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{cursor}\{row, col\}}
                \col{Position cursor}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{ansi}\{codes\}}
                \col{ANSI escape sequence}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{main}\{body\}}
                \col{Interactive main loop}
            }
            \row[frame:{b:single}]{
                \col{\textit{Dynamic Names}}
                \col{}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\verb|${prefix${i}suffix}|}
                \col{Computed variable name}
            }
            \row{
                \col{\cmd{inc}\<*name\>}
                \col{String-based indirection}
            }
        }
    }


@end

#target_prefix " "

#before_each
    \linebreaker{greedy}
    \setwidth{80}
    \setunicode{true}
    \setmathitalic{true}

    \macro<\indented{content}>{\indent[2]{${content}}}
    \macro<\cmd{x}>{\textbackslash{}\textit{${x}}}

    %%% Renders hy as source and rend as an example rendered output
    \macro<\hylst{hy}{rend}>{%
        \fancylisting{${hy}}

        \begin{vbox}
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[3]{}
                    \child{\hrule{╭}{─}{╮}}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child{
                        ╭──┴────────────╮
                    }
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[1]{}
                    \child[15]{
                        \hyades{} Output │
                    }
                    \child{\hrule{|}{·}{|}}
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child{
                        ╰──┬────────────╯
                    }
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[3]{}
                    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
                    \child[1]{}
                    \child{${rend}}
                    \child[2]{}
                    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{░}{}}
                    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[3]{}
                    \child{\hrule{╰}{─}{╯}}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}

            }
        \end{vbox}
    }

    \macro<\didyouknow{content}>{
        \vskip{1}
        \hcenter[60]{
        \hrule{}{.}{}
        ${content}
        \hrule{}{.}{}
        }
    }
#end
